<HEAD>Interest Builds In Possible Cuomo Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``He gets, with
Cuomo comment in Washington Post interview</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> is being courted by candidates and pursued by the press as curiosity mounts over whether he will endorse anyone before his state's important April 19 presidential primary. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s closest advisers insisted Wednesday that they did n't know when or even whether the inscrutable governor would give his blessing to one of the Democrats competing for the party's `` They've made it clear both publicly and privately they want his endorsement,'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> press secretary <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said of the candidates. `` But at this point nothing has changed, despite the 4,000 phone calls we got.'' `` He gets a constant stream of calls from the various candidates,'' said <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> political adviser <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Frucher </PERSON>. `` Obviously, the front-runners have always wanted him to endorse and the others try to keep him from endorsing.'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said in an interview published in Thursday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that he has not ruled out endorsing someone, but added, `` The closer you get to primary day, the less reason'' there is to do so. The newspaper quoted the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> governor as saying he preferred to remain neutral until after the final primaries and then back the leader. `` That's the time for leadership in this process,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, fresh from twin victories this week in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, is seeking to solidify his front-runner status _ and clear his path to the nomination _ with another win over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, for his part, is making a major effort in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to succeed outside his native South. He has not won a contest in a month and is no longer eligible for federal matching funds. There are two reasons candidates are eager for <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s endorsement First, the governor supported <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in the 1984 election and, with the <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> team running his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> campaign, <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> scored a major victory. Second, and perhaps even more important to this year's candidates, a <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> endorsement would reduce speculation that the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> governor is angling for the nomination himself from a deadlocked national convention and that he might be an available alternative for Democrats <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> set off a new round of speculation Tuesday when, asked about a possible <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> endorsement, he chuckled and told reporters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> that he planned to `` talk to you tomorrow.'' But on Wednesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he had nothing new to report. `` I'd like to have it -LRB- <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s endorsement -RRB-. He knows that. But it's his decision to make,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` This is getting to be kind of fun,'' <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said of the interest over what <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> will do. `` Yesterday, we were inundated with a wave of early morning ` he's going to go with the <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION>' calls, all out of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Then, a little bit later in the day, there was a wave of ` he's going with <PERS