<HEAD>60th Academy Awards: The Year Of The Actress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>' 60th awards might well be termed the Year of the Actress, so impressive are the candidates for best performance by an actress in 1987. After being overshadowed for a few decades by macho stars, film actresses are now having powerful roles fashioned for them. This year's nominees afford proof: <PERSON> Cher </PERSON>, the perplexed widow of `` Moonstruck''; <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON>, the vengeful spurned lover in `` Fatal Attraction''; <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, the dynamic news producer of `` Broadcast News''; <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>, the faded Czech actress, `` Anna''; and Meryl Streep, the down-and-out ex-singer in `` Ironweed.'' Adding to their impressive number are performances that many felt warranted Academy consideration: <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Gish </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, `` The Whales of August''; <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, `` Hope and Glory''; <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, `` The Lonely Passion of <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearn </PERSON>''; <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahti </PERSON>, `` Housekeeping''; <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON>, `` Barfly''; Barbra Streisand, `` Nuts''; <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>, `` The Glass Menagerie.'' <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> has been drawing the most attention among the nominees, attracting a media broadside of amazing proportions. The one-time member of the <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> singing team is justifiably proud of her performance in `` Moonstruck'' and has been willing to talk about it. `` ` Moonstruck' is the first movie of mine that I ever watched without wanting to throw up,'' she says. `` I was in love with the story; it's my best work since ` Mask.' `` Usually everyone's first choice is Meryl -LRB- Streep -RRB- and then so-and-so and then so-and-so. It's something to start being someone's first choice. ... <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> has clout, you know. Barbra Streisand has clout. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON> has clout. I think relative to them, I'm a newcomer. ... I'm not working my way toward power. I'm working my way toward the best roles I can get.'' Equally voluble is <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>, who won the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> as best dramatic actress for `` <PERSON> Anna </PERSON>.'' She has been enjoying her success after years of trying: `` I have tested for the leading role in 25 movies, and each time the choice has narrowed to another actress and myself. Each time the other actress won.'' The actress campaigned for the role in the low-budget film, studying the Czech accent and absorbing the atmosphere of the emigre community in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. She even added 15 pounds and taped her face to create wrinkles. Does she want the Oscar? `` I can not tell a lie; my fantasy ever since I was 5 years old has been to hold that -LRB- statue -RRB- and say, ` Thank-you, thank-you, thank-you.''' <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, hailed as a bright new star because of `` Broadcast News,'' has been as silent as <LOCATION> Kirkland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> have been vocal. She declined most interviews, arguing that she was too involved with the <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> play, `` A Lie of the Mind,'' at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' Mark Taper Theater Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> predicts the Georgia-born actress `` will be around for decades.'' Of his script she commented: `` I loved it; I thought it was remarkably three-dimensional.'' She also talked about the differences between herself and the news producer she portrays: `` <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> is certainly less driven than <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>. I think that my priorities are quite a bit different, in that I'm probably retty obsessed myself, but not to such a manic degree.'' After three supporting-actress nominations in six film roles, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON> broke through in the starring category with `` Fatal Attraction.'' She terms the demonic <PERSON> Alix </PERSON> the first woman she's played `` who is out of control, who emotionally runs the gamut _ the first real, full-blooded role I've had. Her comment on the huge reaction to `` Fatal Attraction'': `` The whole male-female thing in this country is very volatile right now. I think many women are feeling used by men. They invest a lot in a relationship, in nurturing a man emotionally and in his career, but they have their own careers and emotions, and they do n't get that nurturing in return.'' After playing a number of glamorous roles, two-time Oscar winner <PERSON> Meryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Streep </PERSON> found her role as the derelict in `` Ironweed'' had its advantages: `` In this world of purgatory of the soul, there are very few markers to go by. I liked that about her. I liked not having to worry about how I looked and being able to strip away, strip away everying, except what counts.'' Streep has created a series of indelible performances, including Oscar winners in `` <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>'' and `` <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON>'s Choice,'' as well as `` The Deer Hunter'' and `` Out of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' She remains ambitious: `` There's so much I'd like to do. When the public is used to you in heavy drama, it's hard to make them take you seriously. But I want to play comedy. `` I ca n't stand it that stage fright inhibits me. At some point I'm going to face up and do a play. But for now I just go day to day.''
