<HEAD>Sinatra, Sammy Davis Swing Radio City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> called himself and <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` the <LOCATION> Springsteen </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of the Geritol set'' Wednesday night as they launched into a `` Guys and Dolls'' medley, the encore in their Rat Pack show. Radio City Music Hall was n't exactly rocking, but it was swinging. The 6,000-seat hall was sold out, with a top ticket price of $ 75. `` Let's not overdo it,'' <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> cautioned as <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, making use of a new hip replacement, did a few dance steps during the encore, `` because I'm tired of working alone.'' <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> had embarked with his old <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> buddies on the so-called Rat Pack tour earlier this year but has been sidelined in recent weeks by kidney problems. `` We check with him every day,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> assured the crowd. `` He is cooking; he'll be back to work soon.'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, as thin as <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> used to be, did the first 40 minutes of the two-hour show. He really sang jazz, and sometimes seemed to be trying to pull the 37-piece band's ponderous arrangements up to his swinging tempo. He had listeners' fingers snapping to `` Satin Doll,'' inserted little jokes into the lyrics of `` The Lady Is a Tramp,'' put powerful emotion into `` What Kind of Fool Am I?'' and `` Birth of the Blues'' and made `` Mr. <PERSON> Bojangles </PERSON>'' into a one-act play. He was never slick. <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>'s voice sometimes has a frayed edge but his masterful phrasing and timing of pithy asides are intact. More important, his vocal timbre _ the thing that makes one know it's <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and not <PERSON> Vic </PERSON> <PERSON> Damone </PERSON> or somebody else _ is still there. He sang the `` Soliloquy'' from `` Carousel'' and the audience exploded in applause. In it, he did some of his best singing of the evening. The audience also seemed to appreciate his ambition in choosing this high-quality, lengthy musical passage. Even better moments were <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>'s hard-swinging `` Mack the Knife'' and `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' and the all-time saloon song, `` One More for the Road,'' which he has sung many times but this time also acted. When <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> harmonized beautifully on the final lines of `` The Oldest Established Permanent Floating Crap Game in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' you knew you'd been thoroughly entertained. On their final night in town, Sunday, the Geritol boys will be joined by <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> in a benefit for cancer research.
