<HEAD>`R' Is for Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part III: At One Elementary School, They `Work Magic' With Ritalin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report; Recommended for side-by-side
use with PM-R Is for Ritalin III-Clinic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BIRMINGHAM, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>'s pupils takes the drug Ritalin to calm his hyperactivity and help him pay attention. She challenged a visitor to guess who. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> was the obvious choice. Seated with three other boys at a semicircular desk in a special education class at <ORGANIZATION> Scotch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, the third-grader fidgeted in his chair, got up several times to sharpen his pencil, drummed his fingers, asked questions repeatedly and never seemed to hear the answers. The guess was wrong. Instead, the child on Ritalin was a slender boy with flaming red hair who calmly sailed through a reading comprehension quiz and listened attentively to a lesson on homonyms. <PERSON> Easton </PERSON> says he's doing so well he probably will leave handicapped classes forever in the fall. At Scotch Elementary, they believe in <LOCATION> Ritalin </LOCATION> _ and teachers point to cases like these to vindicate their faith in the controversial drug. Far from thinking Ritalin creates passive `` zombies,'' as some critics have charged, teachers and parents alike in this affluent northwest <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> suburb seem convinced of Ritalin's track record for turning emotional and academic despair into success. Grades and attention span often improve, and some youngsters who might have spent entire school careers isolated in classes for the disabled have managed to rejoin their regular peers with the help of the drug. Most of all, teachers like <ORGANIZATION> Easton </ORGANIZATION> resent the assertion by some that Ritalin is merely a cynical way for schools to silence problem children while claiming they are trying to help them. `` I read that this is the way we treat kids we ca n't handle. It's not true. It's just not true,'' said <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, whose daughter has taken the drug for four years. While an estimated 1-2 percent of the nation's 40 million schoolchildren take Ritalin, Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wender </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> psychiatrist and author of several books on attention deficit disorder, or ADD, believes 3-to-10 percent of all children have hyperactivity problems. At Scotch Elementary, approximately 5 percent of the 550 pupils drop by principal <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Childress </PERSON>'s office each day to take a pill. Several elements help explain why Ritalin is commonplace at Scotch Elementary; teachers and school administrators have attended seminars and taken other training to recognize symptoms of ADD. Area doctors are not only willing to prescribe Ritalin but also to work with teachers and schools to monitor its success. And parents generally seem to accept the professionalism, good faith and judgment of the teachers and doctors. `` When you first start talking to parents about this, they're devastated,'' said principal <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Childress </PERSON> `` Then 90 percent react that it is a medical problem.'' <PERSON> Childress </PERSON> tells of a youngster named <PERSON> George </PERSON> who has taken Ritalin for two years. He had been assigned to a `` resource room,'' where handicapped children get individual instruction for part of each day. `` He had an incident every day of losing his temper, punching someone or screaming in vile terms,'' said <PERSON> Childress </PERSON>. `` Now he's out of special education He's a winner.'' <PERSON> Childress </PERSON>, like other educators, insists `` we never recommend medication.'' But that's only partly true. If the school's psychologist, social worker or reading specialist believes a child has ADD, they know which doctors will nearly always prescribe Ritalin At the top of the list is Dr. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Robin </PERSON>, a pediatrician who operates the <ORGANIZATION> Attention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deficit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in nearby <LOCATION> Southfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. Schools from all over <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> recommend her, and prospective patients often wait 6-8 weeks for an appointment She now treats 1,500 youngsters for ADD, some as young as 3. Almost invariably, she prescribes Ritalin or similar medication. `` I work magic with the medicine,'' she said in an interview in her office. `` I'm willing to try things. `` We're talking about large numbers of kids who are getting a bum steer in life, from kindergarten on. Some look like couch potatoes. They do n't all look alike,'' she said. But even Ritalin's advocates admit it is n't always well-monitored. Teachers are supposed to provide crucial information enabling doctors to set the right dosage, or to determine if drugs are necessary at all to academic success. Such monitoring is frequent when medication first begins. After that, `` there really is n't that much to do unless there's a problem,'' the doctor said. <PERSON> Childress </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> and other ADD specialists typically send teachers questionnaires to fill out for the first 2-4 weeks of medication, then gradually less frequently until `` we feel we're on a steady course. At a certain point we step out of the picture unless the teacher notices a problem.'' Still, Ritalin remains a `` last resort,'' said <PERSON> Childress </PERSON>. Teachers might, for example, put distractible children in study carrels _ desks with three sides blocked off so the child ca n't see in front or to either side. But when `` we've exhausted all those things ... logged the classroom observations,'' <PERSON> Childress </PERSON> said, `` we would just as soon get a recommendation to try something else.''
