<SECOND>PM-Ritalin-Utah,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowded Classrooms, Large Families in No. 1 Ritalin State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-R Is for Ritalin III</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> is a state of large, close-knit families whose religion frowns on the use of liquor and caffeine. It is also a state with the nation's largest appetite for the stimulant drug Ritalin. The <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said that in 1986 pharmacies along the state's <ORGANIZATION> Wasatch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> received 25,000 grams of the drug used for hyperactive children, or 1,558 grams for every 100,000 population. That figure compares to 1,218 grams per 100,000 residents of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, the next highest Ritalin state. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the figure was 347 grams per 100,000. The reasons for <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s high use of Ritalin are many. They may point the way for the future in other parts of the country. `` What we are doing here is, in some ways, ahead of many parts of the country,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wender </PERSON>, a psychiatrist and researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> has the youngest population of any state, with nearly a quarter of its residents aged 5 to 17. It also leads the nation in the size of individual families, about 4.3 children per household. Consequently it has the nation's most crowded classrooms with 24.6 students per teacher. Although <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> ranks near the top of the list in the amount of state money, 47 percent, going to education, it is last in per capita spending on education, at $ 2,372 per student. So when the fragile balance in these overcrowded classrooms is threatened by disruptive children, `` the pressures on parents and teachers are going to lead people to look for solutions ... and one of the solutions is medication,'' said <PERSON> Stevan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kukic </PERSON>, state director of special education. In the <ORGANIZATION> Salt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, an estimated 2 percent of the 60,000 students receive Ritalin or one of its cousins for attention deficit disorder, a syndrome that includes hyperactive as well as inattentive pupils. `` It is becoming more acceptable in the parents' minds and the teachers' minds,'' said <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a special education teacher whose son takes Ritalin. `` When the teachers see the dramatic effect it can have on problem students, they want them medicated so they can learn.'' <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>, a psychologist who saw 100 ADD children at his clinic last year, estimates a quarter of his patients are referred by the schools. Another 25 percent come at the suggestion of other parents whose children take Ritalin. Half his patients were sent by pediatricans. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s medical community also contributes to Ritalin use. Reseachers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> are considered leaders in ADD study. Their philosophies are passed on to their students, many of whom later set up practice nearby. As a result, <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> has three clinics that specialize in the diagnosis and treatment of ADD children _ many larger cities across the country have none. Psychologists, psychiatrists and pediatricians share information and refer patients for treatment. `` In a community this size it is easier to make an impact with an idea, especially an idea that appeals to people,'' said <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>. Parents of ADD children describe their successes with Ritalin as more than appealing. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Miner </PERSON> cries when she talks about the effect Ritalin has had on her 11-year-old son, <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON>. `` There has been such a remarkable change in this child,'' she said. `` From the time he was 7 he talked about suicide. Now he's on the student council and is so thrilled with life.'' Mrs. Miner has joined others in a local support group for ADD parents. The gatherings can be emotional: laughter about the bruises and stitches their children have collected while rocketing around the house, tears as they talk about the difference treatment has brought. `` I wanted to share the knowledge with other families,'' said the group's founder, <PERSON> Terri </PERSON> <PERSON> Steineckert </PERSON>, whose son, <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, 11, has taken Ritalin for more than a year. `` It is very traumatic to put a child on drugs, but if you have a good experience, you're converted,'' she said
