<HEAD>Overseas Arrests of Americans Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of Americans caught in foreign drug busts jumped 22 percent last year, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported in an effort to scare <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tourists out of taking controlled substances on overseas vacations. `` As we approach the busy travel season, many Americans are getting ready for that long-awaited trip abroad; for some, the trip will become a nightmare,'' the department said Tuesday in a report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Police abroad seized 1,242 Americans on drug charges last year, compared with 1,013 in 1986, the report said. The biggest increases in drug-related arrests of Americans were in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, where governments are under pressure from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to get tough on narcotics. Of the 3,041 Americans taken into custody in foreign countries, 41 percent were suspected of drug violations. `` Americans have been arrested for possessing as little as a third of an ounce of marijuana,'' the report said. It added: `` Those Americans who assume there is no real danger in buying or carrying just a ` small' amount of drugs on their overseas trip may be in for a very unpleasant surprise. `` Many travelers also assume that, as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens, they are immune from prosecution under foreign laws.'' That was underscored Tuesday by a Spanish court's conviction of <PERSON> Conan </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, a 23-year-old <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> photographer, on cocaine importation charges. Despite <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government belief that <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> was an innocent traveler duped by an acquaintance into carrying the drugs into <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, he was sentenced to six years in jail. The 10 countries that arrested the most Americans on all charges last year were <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, 990; <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, 346; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 267; the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, 196; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 128; <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, 124; the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, 74; <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, 60; <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, 53 and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, 52. At year's end, 596 Americans were serving jail sentences overseas. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> have inmate transfer treaties that permit offenders to serve their sentences in jails in their homeland, but fewer prisoners than normal were able to return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal prisons did n't have enough space Riots among Cubans at federal penitentiaries in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, aggravated the crowding. The largest number of inmate mistreatment complaints from Americans abroad came from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, notably those in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> prison near <LOCATION> Hermosillo </LOCATION>. About one-fourth of the 164 Americans arrested in that area of northern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> complained of mistreatment and `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials found such reports credible and made a vigorous formal protest in August,'' the report said. Since then, no reports of mistreatment at that prison have been received, the report said. Several countries prevented <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to Americans with dual nationality. TheSoviet Union, as in the past, refused to grant access to three prisoners with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nationality and obstacles also were raised in cases in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, the report said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> also received complaints from American tourists detained at the border for alleged customs violations. Most of the Americans were fined in dollars _ scarce currency in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> _ and released within 24 hours. The number of Americans incarcerated in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> declined last year, mostly because that country relaxed punishments against foreigners accused of breaking the Islamic ban on alcoholic beverages. Instead of sentencing liquor possessors to jail, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> now usually deports them, the report said. Americans in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> benefited from a round of pardons granted on the 60th birthday of the king. Several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisoners were released and a few others had their sentences reduced. Still, 30 Americans remained in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s `` substandard'' prisons at the end of the year. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spent $ 46,000 on medical assistance and food for needy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisoners, more than $ 20,000 of which went to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> inmates in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, according to the report.
