 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> appealed to the <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> people's congresses to support Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s stated aim to abolish the death penalty in the north African nation. The London-based human rights organization said the <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader called on the people's congresses to hold a special session soon to discuss his proposed changes in human rights' laws, including the abolition of the death penalty. The congresses are supposed to have absolute power over government policy under the socialist system devised by <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> in 1977. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> opposes the death penalty as cruel, inhuman and degrading punishment. Its abolition, the organization said in a statement Tuesday, would be a `` major step in the respect of human rights by the Libyan Jamahiriya,'' or `` the masses,'' which is how <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> refers to itself.
