<HEAD>Spiffy `USA Today - The Television Show' Previewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's fast, it's colorful, it's as spiffy as can be. It's `` USA Today'' on TV. Executive producer <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> unveiled a prototype of the syndicated, daily television show and his four-person anchor team Tuesday at one of a series of news conferences, this one in the Rainbow Room, upstairs from his old office at <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> where he was executive producer of `` Today.'' `` <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> _ The Television Show'' premieres on Sept. 12, but is already a hit, having been sold in 118 markets covering 85 percent of the country. That gives it, higher coverage than any syndicated show except `` Wheel of Fortune,'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. The promotional reel <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> showed reporters promised stations considering buying the show that it would take them `` into the'90s.'' `` It's a fast-paced world and I think a lot of the media has n't caught up,'' said <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, after showing the tape The pace of the promotional show, complete with commercials, was fast to spin heads. Not surprisingly, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> assured reporters that `` USA Today'' wo n't be a `` traditional'' news show but rather will rely on upbeat human-interest stories, polls and interviews. Since it's based on the colorful, successful, young national newspaper, it `` does n't have any baggage from the past,'' he said. `` We do n't have to worry about what <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON> said.'' The show is the first product from <ORGANIZATION> GTG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>, the partnership between former <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinker </PERSON>, who is also former president of <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, the publisher of <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> and the nation's largest newspaper group. GTG is also producing network entertainment shows. `` <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> _ The Television Show'' will be a half hour daily, an hour on weekends. The show will be fed to stations each day via satellite at 4:30 p.m. Eastern time. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said 96 of the stations will broadcast the show in what he considers its ideal time period, the hour between the evening news and the beginning of prime time. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> has assembled a good-looking cast of network veterans to anchor the four segments, based on the four sections of the newspaper: <PERSON> Edie </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> from <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> as `` Front Page'' anchor; <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, also formerly with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, as `` Money'' editor; <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Macatee </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> for `` Sports'' and <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, also formerly with <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, for `` Life.'' The show will preview the next day's edition of `` USA Today,'' but not necessarily have the same stories as the newspaper. `` It will be topical, but to be successful it will have to be different,'' said <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON>. `` We will be doing what would be the next day's lead the night before.'' <PERSON> Macatee </PERSON> suggested he might have coaches other than baseball managers wear uniforms for a segment. `` Or let's have the head of an airline dress like a pilot for a day to see how it fits, see how people react,'' he said. A daily poll will be the centerpiece of the show, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. The promotional tape featured a poll on marriage, using clips from movies to illustrate the results, for example, `` Body Heat'' illustrating a question about infidelity. Academy Award-winning composer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, who wrote the theme, was featured in an interview in the promotional tape describing the music, much like the show, as having `` a happy, laid-back feeling, but with a sense of urgency.'' <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> is n't the only newspaper getting into the act. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION>, which has a radio show, is holding a news conference later this week to announce its own television show.
