<FIRST>r i PM-GassingVictims     04-06 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gassing Victims,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outlook Clouded For Poison Gas Victims of Iran-Iraq War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hands shielding swollen eyes from the glare of television lights, the three little girls squirmed uncomfortably in the hospital room as they were displayed as survivors of a poison gas attack. The girls are among five victims being treated in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for chemical burns to the lung, eyes and skin. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> says they are survivors of a March 16 chemical attack by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> on the Kurdish village of <LOCATION> Halabjah </LOCATION>. Four of them met reporters Tuesday in an event organized by the Iranian mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the arena for a bitter propaganda war between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> enemies have been fighting for 7 -LCB- years. One patient, <PERSON> Nazanin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON>, 30, was not shown to reporters because she is in the intensive care unit. The <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> government says <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> bombed its own citizens with chemical weapons _ killing 5,000 and injuring 7,000 _ after members of the restive Kurdish minority welcomed invading Iranian troops to <LOCATION> Halabjah </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Azizi </PERSON>, a 25-year-old university student, said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> forces attacked the village several times in response to Kurdish unrest. But <PERSON> Azizi </PERSON> said even from the shelter of his basement, he knew the March 16 attack was different. `` We smelled the gas,'' he explained through an intepreter. `` We knew it was not the other kind of bomb,'' the ordinary kind. <PERSON> Azizi </PERSON> said from his hospital bed that when he ventured outside hours later, he saw streets strewn with the victims of what doctors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> suspect was mustard gas, a World War I weapon outlawed worldwide since 1925. `` Any door you opened there were children, men and women, dying, dead,'' <PERSON> Azizi </PERSON> said, his words punctuated by rough coughs. `` I saw a lot of people in cars. As many as 10, 11, 12 in a car. They were dying.'' He said he and other stunned survivors began streaming out of <LOCATION> Halabjah </LOCATION>. `` We tried to run out,'' <ORGANIZATION> Azizi </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We did n't want to see that.'' But he said that once outside, he was soon sickened by the gas. `` My eyes felt heavy. It was hard to breathe. Eight or nine times I threw up. I smelled gas,'' he recounted. Doctors at St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Episcopal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s borough of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, said all five of those brought to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> suffered lung and eye damage and from burns One child is also showing signs of bone marrow damage, said Dr. <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Lief-Dienstag </PERSON>, head of the pediatrics department. She said the long-term prognogis for a gassing victim is unclear. `` I can tell you what a gunshot wound is. I can tell you what's going to happen to the patient,'' she said `` But I do n't know what's going to happen to these children. I do n't know what's going to happen to their lungs in six months and I do n't think anyone else does either, including all the experts we've spoken to.'' Dr. <PERSON> Lief-Dienstag </PERSON>'s young patients were clearly uneasy when Iranian officials escorted journalists to their room. Several doctors expressed concern about infection. One, speaking on condition he not be identified, said emphatically that the news media visit `` was n't our idea.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> transferred small contingents of survivors from hospitals in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> to hospitals in major <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> cities and to St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s. Dr. <PERSON> Meyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Atabaki </PERSON>, an Iranian who is an attending physician at St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s, said all five brought to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> had to be sedated at first before they could be treated. `` They cried for 24 hours after they got here,'' Dr. <PERSON> Lief-Dienstag </PERSON> said. Hospital officials say psychiatrists are following the progress of all five patients, particularly the children, who were orphaned by the attack. `` They are innocent bystanders who ... were in the wrong place at the wrong time,'' Dr. <PERSON> Lief-Dienstag </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Javan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdollah </PERSON>, 12, and her sister, <PERSON> Rezen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdollah </PERSON>, 9, and <PERSON> Kobra </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON>, also 9. Dr. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, head of the department of medicine, said he and the other doctors at St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s consulted experts in chemical injuries from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ghent </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Amir </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamani </PERSON>, a first secretary at the Iranian mission, said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> sent about 100 victims to hospitals abroad because <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s hospitals ran out of room. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, which earlier confirmed several Iraqi attacks with outlawed mustard gas and nerve gas during the war, has sent a team to investigate the <LOCATION> Halabjah </LOCATION> attack. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, meanwhile, is accusing <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of using the banned weapons. On Monday, it asked for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team to go to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to examine 88 soldiers it says were gassed.
