 Ground personnel at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> airport announced they will stage 12-hour strikes on April 16 and 24. The Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> said the strikes are expected to force the cancellation or postponement of most flights on those two days. Union leaders on Tuesday said the strike would not interfere with flights for emergency, military or government purposes. Flights to and from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s islands also will not be interrupted. Waves of recent airline and railway strikes in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> over the last five months have made traveling difficult to plan. Ground crews have been negotiating for a new contract for eight months. For the last five months, the crews have staged periodic strikes. They are demanding better working conditions in the control towers, salary increases and fewer hours in the work week.
