<FIRST>r w PM-WorldTaxes     04-06 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Taxes,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Countries Follow U.S. Drop in Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Income tax cuts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have encouraged cuts in 10 other major countries, according to a study distributed by the Brookings Institution. `` The movement ... also reflects the almost universal recognition of the distortions and inequities created by high tax rates, years of inflation and ineffective tax preferences,'' says <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pechman </PERSON>, president-elect of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, who edited the report. Brookings is a private policy-research organization. Its study includes analyses by tax officials from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It does not deal with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has announced a plan for a progressive income tax _ higher taxes on higher incomes. It comes just as non-communist countries are making their rates less progressive. None of the new top rates in the 10 non-communist countries is as low as the 33 percent that goes into effect for this year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 1984 top rate of 88 percent will be down to 76 percent by 1990 and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s 56 percent is dropping to 53 percent. The highest French rate is going down to 57 percent from 65 percent while <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s is dropping from 65 to 60 percent. Of the 10, only <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top rate of 60 percent will hold steady from 1984 to 1990. It was reduced from 83 percent in 1979, when Conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> embraced the tax cut movement. One contributor to the study, <PERSON> Sijbren </PERSON> <PERSON> Cnossen </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Erasmus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, criticizes the flattening of rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` In most European countries ... it has long been realized that poverty issues must largely be addressed through the welfare system,'' he writes. `` As a result of these countries' pervasive social security systems, the income distribution has become much less unequal than, say 40 years ago.'' He does not mention <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where the social security system is weak compared to those of western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He says the European arrangements have benefits and costs not yet fully understood. `` The system appears to be headed for a significant overhaul as populations age rapidly in the next 30 years,'' he predicts. An overview of the world tax situation was given by <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Messere </PERSON> from the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the `` rich man's club'' of governments in western industrialized countries. `` Though vertical equity -LRB- progressive taxation -RRB- has been thrown out of the tax policy door, it is lurking in some areas of tax reform _ the idea being not to soak the relatively few rich, but to protect the many poor,'' he says. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> take the view that the poor should not pay income tax. ... <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> believe all or nearly all citizenas should contribute ... even if they get more back in transfer payments than they pay in taxes.''
