<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> voters Tuesday elected a mayor who promised `` real change'' after retiring Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maier </PERSON>'s nearly three decades in office, and voters in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, unseated their Republican mayor. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s clout was demonstrated in defeat of a charter amendment in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, while in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, Mayor <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> survived a recall election that resulted from a controversy with racial overtones. <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> swept to victory over former acting Gov. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON> in the non-partisan race to succeed <PERSON> Maier </PERSON>, who is retiring at age 70 after holding the office since 1960. `` Together we built a grass-roots volunteer organization like <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> has never seen,'' <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> told cheering backers at his victory party. `` Together we delivered a message of hope ... and a message of real change. And together we will make this message a reality in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>.'' Complete, unofficial returns from all 324 precincts showed the 38-year-old <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> with 112,902 votes, or 54 percent, and <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON> with 93,738 votes, or 45 percent. Roughly 26 percent of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>'s registered voters turned out for the charter referendum. Unofficial returns showed 46,854 votes against the measure, or 65 percent, to 25,458 in favor, or 35 percent. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential contender, lent his support to opponents of the amendment to limit the city council president to two one-year terms. The ballot issue was viewed by many as an attack on City Council President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON>, who has led the council for 15 years and is the city's highest black elected official. The <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ordinance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reforming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s Efficiency, known as C-Force, led a petition drive to get the amendment on the ballot. C-Force leaders, including blacks, contend <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON> has intimidated council members by withholding federal money for ward projects and stalling legislation. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s picture was used on literature against the amendment and a radio advertisement featured <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> urging voters to defeat the charter amendment. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> recorded an audio tape in which he claims that Tuesday's special election on the amendment is an attempt `` to take away what we have gained across the years _ a share of power in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and across the nation,'' said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s national campaign manager <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> mayor <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a 59-year-old self-employed tree surgeon elected as a write-in candidate in 1986, faced a recall election because of controversy over remarks he made last October at a meeting with local blacks angry over the forced resignation of Police Chief <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Dye </PERSON>, a black. The mayor, who is white, told a predominantly black crowd that if they did n't like <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> they ought to leave. `` In the annals of black history, we are always told to move and give up our rights,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, a leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concerned </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION>, which organized the recall drive. Final returns showed 2,493 voters, or 22 percent, favored recalling the self-employed tree surgeon while 9,041 voters, or 78 percent, wanted him to remain in office. Five candidates were running for mayor in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, where a number of other local offices were being decided. Final unofficial returns showed state Sen. <PERSON> Rodger </PERSON> <PERSON> Randle </PERSON>, a Democrat, had 45,517 votes, or 55.3 percent, to <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> incumbent <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>'s 28,142 votes, or 34.2 percent. In <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, a city rocked by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s announced closing of an auto plant, incumbent Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorff </PERSON> lost a bid to win his first full term. With 33 of 34 precincts reporting, unofficial returns showed <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> with 12,329 votes to 10,130 for <PERSON> Dorff </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, support in the black community became a heated campaign issue. When black businessman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON>, who finished third in the Feb. 16 primary, held a rally to endorse a candidate while paying off remaining campaign debts, <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> boycotted the event and its $ 20 admission fee. <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON> attended and won the endorsement. <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> was elected to the state Assembly in 1974 and served there until being elected in 1982 to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where he was assistant majority leader. <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON>, a lawyer, served in the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from 1962 until being elected lieutenant governor in 1970, then was acting governor after Gov. <PERSON> Patrick </