<HEAD>Former Siamese Twins Going Home To West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, who spent their first seven months joined at the head, are seriously underdeveloped but have the potential to lead normal lives, said doctors preparing to release the babies from the hospital. The separated Siamese twins, now 14 months old, will return to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in the next few days, physicians at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> should begin crawling soon and will go home to Ulm, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with his parents. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> will go to a German hospital for observation. `` There is no reason for us to think they will not continue to improve,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, a member of the medical team that has treated the infants since they were admitted in August. `` They have made very substantial progress in the past few months and ... we're very hopeful the potential will culminate in normal existence,'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said at a news conference. However, Dr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> stressed that the boys are not now normal. Their development is equivalent to that of 2-to-5-month-old babies. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said he was unwilling to project the mental and physical level the boys will reach, but when the twins return here for evaluation next year, doctors will be able to predict fairly accurately the boys' future development. The twins have had several setbacks since they were separated in a 22-hour operation during the Labor Day weekend by a 70-member medical team. In October, their temperatures rose inexplicably for several days. The latest occurred March 13 when <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> choked on formula fed to him through a nasal tube. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said it's unknown if the incident will have long-term effects, although <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> had reached the point of turning over before the incident and has not returned to that level. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> is at about the level as when he entered the hospital and is expected to begin crawling soon, the doctors said. Because they were joined at the head, the twins were not normally developed when they arrived. The trauma of the operation and long hospital stay account at least partially for the developmental lag, <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said. At the time of the separation operation, doctors had given it a 50-50 chance of success. `` Certainly in terms of a medical or technical feat, it has clearly been successful,'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said. He said there were 48 cases in medical history of Siamese twins joined at the head. This was the first separation where both twins lived. Their kind of joining _ at the back of the head with a shared vein _ was the rarest, he said. In February, doctors implanted titanium mesh plates in the opening at the back of their heads, created by the separation of their joined skulls and a shared vein. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> has a bald spot on the back of his head from the operation, ` but if he grows his hair long he can comb it down,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Dufresne </PERSON>. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> has a full head of hair. The twins' parents have refused to speak with reporters here. Before the separation at Hopkins they sold their story to a West German magazine. Their mother, <PERSON> Theresia </PERSON> <PERSON> Parlagi </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, has been at the hospital with the boys and has taken <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> outside in a carriage, doctors said Tuesday. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said the doctors donated all their time and care and <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> treated the boys at no cost except for a small portion of the about $ 800,000 expense covered by German government insurance.
