<HEAD>Opposition Newspaper Suspends Publication; Blames Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, which reopened six months ago after a government-ordered shutdown, said it will cease publishing indefinitely today because the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have withheld newsprint. The leftist government, which controls the purchase and sale of newsprint in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, said its supply was exhausted and claimed it had warned newspapers to conserve paper until a new shipment arrives later this month. `` La Prensa suspends publication,'' said the banner headline in Tuesday's editions of the afternoon newspaper. `` Future undecided because of state control of paper,'' read another headline. `` We do n't have paper to publish tomorrow or on the following days because the government alleges that there is n't any paper in the country, but we know there is,'' said <PERSON> Cristiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, assistant director of <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>. The Ministry of Industry said in a statement in Tuesday morning papers that it did n't have newsprint because a shipment scheduled for March has been delayed. It said a shipment was expected by April 17. `` Once this shipment is received, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> will proceed to distribute paper proportionally according to the established mechanisms,'' it said. The ministry said it told <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> and two other newspapers, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuevo </PERSON> <PERSON> Diario </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barricada </PERSON>, that `` the contraction of paper for the year had suffered delays and that all possible efforts were being made to assure the first shipment during the month of May.'' It said the government had urged the papers to take precautions against using up their s