<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Between Sandinistas and Rebels Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Military leaders for the Sandinista government and the Contra rebels have renewed cease-fire negotiations to hammer out key details for an agreement to end a grueling war now in its seventh year. Little progress was reported Tuesday during 2 -LCB- hours of talks in this remote outpost near the Costa Rican border. Both sides accused the other of misinterpreting a peace plan signed two weeks ago and of violating a truce that started March 21. The only positive aspect of Tuesday's meeting was an agreement to continue the talks until the mechanics of the cease-fire can be worked out. The discussions were resuming today. Hopes for the peace agreement signed March 23 started to fade over the weekend when the U.S.-backed Contras postponed a meeting scheduled for today in the capital of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> between high-ranking government and rebel officials. The Sandinistas argued that the meeting should be held because it was set out in the peace agreement. In putting off the talks, the Contras cited, among other things, the lack of progress in the technical meetings held last week. The talks Tuesday and today were held to define zones in which the rebels are to gather, outline security measures and detail how supplies will be delivered during the 60-day cease-fire, which formally started on Friday. <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, a director of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella group, said the main concern is to `` guarantee the physical security and morale of the Contras.'' He described the talks as `` extremely delicate.'' Contra spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> said the rebel delegation accused the Sandinista troops of systematically violating the truce, which was agreed on March 21 at the start of the three days of talks that led to the signing of the peace plan. He said the Sandinista forces fired mortars and long-range artillery into areas proposed as cease-fire zones for the rebels. `` We consider this part of the strategy to wear down the resistance's forces,'' he told journalists at the meeting at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Sandinista </LOCATION> delegation's leader, denied any cease-fire violations. But he acknowledged that last week there were `` small incidents.'' He said that was `` practically inevitable'' as long as the two sides were not separated and their armies roamed the rural mountains, plains and jungle. The government-run newspapers have charged the Contras with breaking the cease-fire. Both sides offered differing views on the major issue of the laying down of arms, which is not specifically dealt with in the cease-fire agreement. <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> called it `` indispensable, a basic condition'' for the plan to work. The Contra combatants, pointing to the vast number of Nicaraguans carrying arms supplied by the government, say they will never put down their weapons. `` As long as there is no real democracy, there will be no laying down of arms,'' said <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>. `` When there is reconciliation, the arms wo n't be necessary.'' The Contra leaders proposed April 12 instead of today for the next high-level meeting. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> suggested Saturday or April 15. The two sides ca n't agree on how the visit will be handled. The rebels are insisting on free movement during their stay in the capital, saying they want to meet with a variety of opposition groups. The government claims it has to guard their security. <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> said, `` It's not a visit for a political campaign.'' The Sandinistas, who came to power in a 1979 revolution, signed the peace agreement at a time when they faced strong internal political, social and economic pressures. The government, backed by the Soviet bloc, retreated on several hard-line positions. They had vowed never to hold talks with the rebels, discuss internal policies or start political amnesty proceedings. The first 100 of 3,310 political prisoners were released March 29 in accordance with the peace agreement. The Contras approached the pact at a time of improved battlefield strength. But they saw the last of their U.S.-supplied military aid expire at the end of February. In signing the accord, the Contras agreed to accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
