<FIRST>r a PM-SequoiaLogging     04-06 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sequoia Logging,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Logging Halt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plan to clear hundreds of square miles of timber around giant redwoods in <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> was halted by a federal appeals court, which said the government approved the logging too hastily. But the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>' ruling on Tuesday came too late to block logging of about half the non-redwood timber in widely scattered areas of the forest. A different panel of the court refused to halt that operation last December while the appeal was pending. `` If you were a tourist in a redwood grove of the <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, instead of finding a lush natural-vegetation forest you would find dirt and redwood trees alone,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, a lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, which went to court last May to block the logging. `` They're going in with tractors and removing everything from brush to pine to oak,'' he said. The court ordered a ban on further logging in seven tracts in the forest 200 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, saying the government approved an untested logging plan without a proper environmental analysis. An industry spokesman, however, claimed victory because all logging was not banned around the towering sequoias, some of them 400 to 500 years old. `` The forest is not shut down and the mills are going to continue to operate,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Haglund </PERSON>, who represented <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is a much more limited injunction than the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> sought. It's much more of a victory for us than it is for them.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> went to court after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decided that nine timber sale contracts would cause no significant damage and would not require full-scale environmental impact statements assessing the effects on the forest. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> last fall refused to halt the logging, saying the dispute was one over management of the forest. The environmental group appealed. <PERSON> Haglund </PERSON> said Tuesday's injunction prevents logging of about 9 million board-feet of timber, at least temporarily until an environmental plan is developed. In a five-year plan covering the entire forest, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> proposes logging of 80 million to 90 million board-feet a year, <PERSON> Haglund </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> had hoped the court would address the five-year plan for the entire forest, a subject not mentioned in the ruling. But <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said the ruling at least will require the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to take review the plan. In approving the clear-cutting plan, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said it would help to regenerate the redwoods by creating areas of bare mineral soil and sunlight. But the court quoted a professional forester as saying the method was experimental and unproven. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said experts have told him it ultimately would destroy the redwoods. `` By tractor-logging, almost assuredly you will end up with damage to the roots ... and often exposure of the roots,'' he said. `` The other problem is tremendous soil compaction. The water that normally would hit the ground and percolate down and provide nourishment instead erodes off of the land.''
