ecurity men and two pedestrians were killed along with the bomber. The terrorist attacks have included bombings and the hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jetliner in 1984. In that incident, two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> passengers were slain by the hijackers, who demanded freedom for 17 pro-Iranian extremists imprisoned in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> for bombing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies and other targets in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> in 1983. The Arabs who hijacked the Kuwaiti airliner Tuesday made the same demand. The fundamentalist <PERSON> Islamic </PERSON> rulers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, who have been at war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for 7 -LCB- years, accuse <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> of aiding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Members of the <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON> clan fill most senior posts in the government, the army, the police and both the private and public sectors of the emirate, which has a population of 1.7 million. They include the crown prince and prime minister, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Saad </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Salem </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON>, and the ministers of defense, interior, foreign affairs and information. Even the hijacked plane is named after the ruler and has the word <PERSON> Al-Jaberiya </PERSON>, Arabic for `` the plane of the Al-Jabers,'' emblazoned on its side.
