 way these interests can be served.'' At the same time, he said negotations must be based on <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolutions that call on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to yield territory captured in the 1967 war in exchange for peace. Without explanation, the interview was not shown on Jordanian television Tuesday night. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Tuesday that both <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> were prepared to hold negotiations with <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> on an overall settlement. `` But there are all sorts of questions,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, especially on how negotiations on Palestinian self-rule would be linked to dealing with an overall settlement. `` I do n't want to give any big plus sign because that would not be warranted by the facts,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Damascus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> made four demands in connection with a peace settlement, including complete <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> withdrawal from the occupied lands and establishment of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state.
