<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge denied a request by jurors for a trial transcript, telling them to rely on memory and notes while deliberating in the case of 13 white supremacists, including nine accused of sedition. Deliberations were delayed today because one of the jurors has a sick child. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said juror <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittenburg </PERSON> went to a hospital to see about his baby and that the third day of deliberations was postponed until he could rejoin the jury. Nine defendants are charged with conspiring to overthrow the government by violence, and one of them, along with four other defendants, is charged with conspiring to kill a federal judge and an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent. Two of the sedition defendants are accused of the interstate transportation of stolen money. In denying three jurors' requestion for the transcript Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said the document would be 7,000 pages long and would not be ready for three or four months. He also denied their request to re-hear lengthy portions of testimony. The government called 113 witnesses and the defense had 79 in the trial which began Feb. 16. The case went to the jury Monday afternoon and lawyers, defendants and others waited at the federal courthouse on Tuesday. One defendant, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, is serving a 150-year sentence for violating the civil rights of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> radio talk show host <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> by killing him, and 100 years on a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> conviction for racketeering. Defendant <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, free on $ 50,000 bond, said he would have attended the trial even if he were not a defendant. `` I would n't have missed it for the world,'' he said. `` This is where the devil is. This is evil personified, the whole crew.'' Defendant <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said the trial is a move by the government to snuff out views that do not meet government approval. He said he expects to be acquitted, `` but in any case, they win: They break us financially.'' <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who also is on trial and is being held without bond, are considered three of the top leaders of the white-supremacist movement in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But one of <PERSON> Beam </PERSON>'s lawyers, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> are `` through fighting. Miles is 63. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> is 70. Beam has got a 20-year-old wife.'' Acquittal would slow the movement, <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said, because it would show that white supremacists `` can get a fair trial in American courts.'' The sedition defendants face up to 20 years in prison and a $ 20,000 fine if convicted. The murder charge carries a maximum of life imprisonment and the interstate transportation charges have a maximum term of 10 years and a $ 10,000 fine. The government also contends that some of the defendants committed a series of robberies to finance their activities. The robberies netted about $ 4.1 million, of which about $ 1 million is unaccounted for, the government said. The key government witness, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON>, testified that the white supremacist group he led in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> carried out bombings to advance a conspiracy begun in July 1983 at <LOCATION> Hayden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, at an Aryan Nations conference. <PERSON>