<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation. April 4 The <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> on <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>: When a high official's political foes call for his resignation, he does well to ignore them. But when political friends urge him to leave, he ought to pay attention. Unfortunately, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> insists on hanging on to his job by his fingernails, despite well-intentioned advice by respected associates that he no longer can fulfill his important duties. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, the Artful Dodger of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, has had a special prosecutor on his tail for much of the four years he has been the nation's highest law enforcement officer. That does n't seem untoward to him, but it does to many of us We know a defendant must be presumed innocent until proven guilty. But the attorney general should be presumed honorable, clean and competent, which his top aides at Justice decline to do. Time to go, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 2 <LOCATION> Evansville </LOCATION> -LRB- Ind. -RRB- Courier on privatization of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service: In a report more likely to gather dust than to trigger immediate action, a presidential commission has come up with an intelligent plan for privatizing the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service. Opponents of privatization point out that the existing government monopoly subsidizies the extra costs of rural mail delivery with revenues from urban and suburban delivery. They predict that if private delivery companies were allowed to enter the market, they would concentrate only on high-volume, low-cost areas and leave the Feds stuck with the unprofitable rural routes. The commission's response: Start by allowing free competition only in rural delivery. If private companies succeed in serving rural households at prices no higher than those of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, `` this strategy could go a long way toward calming the fears of rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that postal privatization would leave them underserved.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s successor should see to it that the experiment gets a chance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 5 The Miami News on U.S.-Panama relations: The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> huffed when it indicted Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on drug trafficking charges. It puffed when it froze Panamanian assets and put tolls in escrow. But <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s house has not fallen down. There is a temptation to use the teeth of the big, bad wolf: <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops. White House sources said over the weekend that intervention was being considered, then settled for sending 1,300 more troops to the Canal Zone for the legitimate purpose of protecting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. But military intervention to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is unwarranted. Besides, huffing and puffing have not yet had enough time to work. Intervention would draw attention away from the cause of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s crisis, which is <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 31 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, on <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>: If -LRB- the -RRB- Justice -LRB- Department -RRB- has been `` functioning just fine,'' we'd hate to see it when it needed a tune-up. Two top officials ... and their four highest aides quit abruptly. -LRB- Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is the focus of protracted criminal investigations by a special prosecutor into two separate cases, <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> oil pipeline. ... The attorney general is the nation's chief law enforcement officer. ... He must also be on top of the day-to-day efforts of the federal government to fight crime. Yet upper management at the department is being decimated, and the man at the very top is preoccupied with extraneous matters and precluded from participating in important issues. The resignations in the department loudly signal the necessity for just one more. ... <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> should quit. Now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 4 The <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> on the legacy of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>: It was 20 years ago today that the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> was gunned down while standing on the balcony of a <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, motel. But, without a doubt, the King legacy lives on. To hear some people speak about him today, one would think the man is still with us. Indeed, that is what legacies are made of. People across the nation will observe this day with marches, rallies and silent prayers. ... While some Americans remain reluctant to admit it, <PERSON> King </PERSON> did much of the work necessary to make this country a better place to live. He is still missed by many.
