SON> Vogel </PERSON>, another witness before the panel on Tuesday who now is serving a 12 -LCB- - year sentence on marijuana charges, said <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> had been arrested along with himself on identical charges, but was dropped from the indictment in March of 1986 while under contract to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` It is unusual. It is strange,'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said. He acknowledged he once had felt bitterness about what he saw as <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>'s preferential treatment, but said he now was more concerned about the corrupting influence of drugs. `` You ca n't use drug smugglers for other tasks by the government,'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> businessman, <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON>, told the panel he had run an honest seafood brokerage enterprise until he was approached in 1986 by <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Merielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Delinois </PERSON>, then <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s wife, about a seafood deal. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> at first offered to sell seafood at below market prices, and asked a $ 1-a-pound commission, he said. But the deal later turned into a drug transaction, and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> arranged for 412 kilos of cocaine to be flown from a grass airstrip on his ranch 90 miles from the Haitian capital, <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> said. When <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> and an associate told <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> they needed a sample of the cocaine, which tested at about 90 percent pure, to take back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the colonel personally carried it past customs officials in his holster for them, <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was able to identify <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug and <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agents in his country because he had a contact inside the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Em