<HEAD>Shiite Militias Fight in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rival Shiite Moslem militias fought in the streets of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Wednesday, the second day of a battle for supremacy in which police say 12 people have been killed and 34 wounded. A police spokesman said the mainstream Amal militia used armored vehicles, artillery, mortars and rocket-propelled grenades against the <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, in 14 towns and villages. Amal is led by <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> justice minister, and has Syrian support. The fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> is loyal to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Militia officers also `` toured the south in loudspeaker vans blaring warnings to <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighters to surrender their weapons and avert the bloodshed,'' the police spokesman said. He quoted Amal as telling <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> gunmen: `` Our main aim is security and stability for the south. Whoever surrenders his weapon will live in peace.'' Fear was expressed in many circles that the war for supremacy in the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> region would spread to the rest of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, which has been ravaged by civil war for 13 years. This led the nation's most leading Shiite cleric, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON>, to order an end to the battle. `` We prohibit this fighting because it burns <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s causes and the Moslems,'' he said in a fatwa, or religious ruling. Despite <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON>'s declaration, <ORGANIZATION> Amal-Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighting raged all day from <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION>, an inland market town, to the ancient port of Tyre. The police spokesman, whose name was withheld in accordance with regulations, gave this account: Amal forces with armored personnel ca