<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,700</SECOND>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with judge's ruling</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra case today ruled he needed more time to study independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s plan to prevent unauthorized disclosure of 150,000 pages of classified documents. In a brief opinion, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> denied <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s motion for expedited consideration of the proposed protective order, saying it `` appears to be far too complex, lacks definite time restrictions and creates undue obstacles to the fair and expeditious disposition of this case.'' But the judge said he wants to set an April deadline for <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s review of the classified material and fix a time for the defense to notify the court whether it intends to use any of the secret documents as evidence <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he would hear further argument at next Tuesday's hearing on `` the timing of discovery disclosures in relation to a realistic trial date. The documents, which <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> says `` describe in detail some of the nation's most carefully held secrets about its foreign policy, its intelligence activities and its covert activities,'' must be turned over to the defense as part of pre-trial discovery. Some of the documents from the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies may be introduced as evidence after they are declassified or secret material is deleted. Lawyers for former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and arms dealers <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> had filed a motion opposing <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s plan to require them and their clients to obtain security clearances to examine the material. The four are accused of conspiracy to defraud the government by diverting arms-sale proceeds to the Nicaraguan rebels. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had sought expedited consideration of his plan by the judge. But <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said: `` It will be necessary to frame a more limited protective order fashioned to the nature of this case, which in essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.'' The proposal includes setting up a `` secure compartmented information facility'' where the defense lawyers would be required to work with the documents and compose any pleadings that quote the material. Without such procedures, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said, he can not begin turning over the material to the defense for pre-trial discovery. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> had also asked <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> to establish intricate procedures under the Classified Information Procedures Act -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> CIPA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- for court review of classified documents to determine how such information could be disclosed in court. The act empowers a trial judge to delete classified portions of a document if it is irrelevent to the case or to substitute a statement of facts that secret material would prove if shown to a jury. In a joint pleading filed Tuesday, defense lawyers opposed <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s motion because it raised questions about `` the constitutionality -LRB- as well as the statutory propriety -RRB- of various aspects of the proposed order even if the <ORGANIZATION> CIPA </ORGANIZATION> itself is constitutional.'' The defense said it wants more time to file briefs on a number of issues it contends are raised by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal. The defense contends that the proposed order would impose `` improper and questionable'' conditions on the defense lawyers and their clients. The defense noted that the order would apply to classified information that had already been known to the defendants, particularly North and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. The attorneys also questioned whether <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, as an independent counsel, has the proper authority to enforce the Classified Information Procedures Act. The defense said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s request raises `` questions whether the president's foreign affairs and national security responsibilities can be delegated to an official such as Mr. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>.'' In reply, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said the defense was attempting `` to invent substantive isues concerning the proposed protective order where none exists.'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> labeled `` transparent'' the defense objection to applying the restrictions to North and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. `` Classified information does not become declassified because a criminal defendant knew it before he was indicted; if that were the case, there would have been no need for the <ORGANIZATION> CIPA </ORGANIZATION> in the many espionage trials where the statute has been used extensively,'' <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said.
