nd reproductive technologies. The dispute began shortly after the child's birth March 31, 1986, when Mrs. <PERSON> Whitehead-Gould </PERSON>, then married to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> and the mother of two, decided to turn down the $ 10,000 surrogacy fee and refused to hand over the child. No money ever changed hands. Mrs. <PERSON> Whitehead-Gould </PERSON> is now expecting her fourth child by her second husband, <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>. The Sterns turned to surrogacy because they feared Mrs. <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, 42, who suffers from a mild form of multiple sclerosis, could develop complications with the disease during pregnancy. Mrs. <PERSON> Whitehead-Gould </PERSON> fled with the baby to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for three months before authorities tracked her down and returned the child to the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON>, setting the stage for the emotional court battle over custody. After a three-month trial, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorkow </PERSON> upheld the surrogate contract and stripped Mrs. <PERSON> Whitehead-Gould </PERSON> of her parental rights, ordering her never to see the child again. The judge then presided over a speedy adoption of the child by Mrs. <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>. But the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned most of Sorkow's ruling in its landmark Feb. 3 ruling The state's highest court outlawed surrogacy-for-pay and restored Mrs. <PERSON> Whitehead-Gould </PERSON>'s parental rights, but upheld custody for the Sterns while ordering the lower court hearing on visitation rights
