<HEAD>Jerry Brown Celebrates 50th Birthday Privately</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, whose unorthodox style and ideas made him one of the nation's hot young politicians in the 1970s, celebrates his 50th birthday Thursday the way he has spent most of the last six years _ in private. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> has been dropping hints in recent months that he plans a comeback, possibly a race for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1992. But he says the time is not yet right to seek the media spotlight again. Therefore, he vetoed plans by a group of friends and supporters for a birthday celebration this week at a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> hotel with 1,000 to 1,500 guests. `` It's just not the right time,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> told reporters. `` If I were more active in the public domain, then it might be appropriate.'' Instead, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> will celebrate Thursday with what he describes as a small family gathering. Reclusiveness has been <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s way since he lost a race for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> six years ago to Republican <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. He has spent most of the past six years traveling, with especially long stays in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and writing a still-unfinished book. That defeat ended eight years in which <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was constantly in the media spotlight with two successful races for governor, two unsuccessful campaigns for the Democratic nomination for president and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> chafed at the constant attention even during the campaign periods when he was working hardest to attract coverage, and he seemed to be genuinely relieved at his close defeat in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race. `` The people ... would like a respite from me, and in some ways, I need a respite from th