 Ammunition exploded at a base for Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> on Wednesday, injuring several people, according to an official report. The blast occurred at the Veszprem base about 60 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, injuring `` several people, including one Hungarian citizen,'' the news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> said in a terse, three-sentence report. It added only that `` the consequences of the explosion have been eliminated.'' There were no details about how the ammunition came to explode, where the incident occurred or how many people were hurt. Veszprem is the largest Soviet troop base in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. There are an estimated 100,000 Soviet soldiers stationed in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nation. <PERSON> Gyula </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, a senior official of the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, told Western reporters last month that there have been talks about withdrawing the Soviet forces. <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said no agreement had been reached.
