<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romania,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budapest Launches Strongest Criticism Yet on Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> on Wednesday launched its strongest criticism yet on communist ally <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> over an ethnic dispute that has clouded relations between the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact neighbors for two years. Two Hungarian newspapers printed editorials fiercely critical of a reported Romanian move to use only Romanian-language place names for cities and villages traditionally known to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s German and Hungarian ethnic minorities in their own languages. About 1.7 million Hungarians and 220,000 ethnic Germans live in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, mostly in the central province of <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has expressed mounting concern over what it says are Romanian moves to cut back Hungarian-language education and disperse the minority throughout <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> charges that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s complaints mask an effort by <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to regain <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>, which was ruled by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for several centuries but given to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> after World War I. Both claim that <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION> is the area where their nations were first settled, and they have squabbled over the region for decades. In the past two years, however, the dispute has escalated, pointing up the difference between <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s reformist communism and the tight rule of President <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, which is increasingly isolated from its East bloc allies. The government daily <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION> said violations of minority rights to maintain their own language and culture can `` neither be understood, or accepted ... at the end of the 20th century on our continent.'' The harsh editorial stopped short of blaming <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> for the move to use only Romanian place names, but said `` it could hardly be a local excess ... -LRB- since -RRB- to our knowledge the strings reach much higher.'' Another daily, <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemzet </ORGANIZATION>, condemned <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>'s recently announced program to wipe out up to 7,000 villages in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> by the year 2000 as `` drastic ... demolition'' and an attempt to quash Romanian, Hungarian and other minority cultures. <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION> also took <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to task for its unprecedented action in denying <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> ambassador a traditional address on national radio and television to mark <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s Liberation Day April 4 The newspaper noted this was a break with tradition, and said without further detail that `` it is regrettable that such themes can emerge between two neighboring Socialist countries.'' Western analysts said Wednesday's attacks were the sharpest yet in the war of words between the nations. Hungarian dissidents, who demonstrated for human rights in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> outside the <ORGANIZATION> Romanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> on Feb. 1, have charged the <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> government is to some extent exploiting popular Hungarian unease about the treatment of ethnic Hungarians in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to divert attention from the country's economic crisis. But <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> took unprecedented action last month when it approved spending about $ 6 million to help an estimated 10,000 refugees who have fled the shortages and harsh living conditions in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Many but not all of the refugees are ethnic Hungarians.
