<HEAD>With PM-Mecham-Mofford, Bjt and PM-Mecham-Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted today to pay former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s $ 202,433 in legal fees for the impeachment trial that removed him from office. The 16-13 vote came shortly before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> formally closed the impeachment trial that began Feb. 29 and resulted in <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s ouster from office on Monday Defense attorney <PERSON> Jerris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to begin a `` healing process'' by paying the fees. `` This has been an agony,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said. `` I think it's the right thing to do ... to show that this body not only has class, but it has heart, it has compassion.'' Republican Sen. <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Lunn </PERSON> agreed, saying it would be a `` magnanimous gesture.'' GOP Sen. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said she thought <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s legal fees should be paid because <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> taxpayers funded the prosecution and trial, and many `` resent deeply their tax dollars being used to convict a governor that they supported.'' However, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mawhinney </PERSON>, also a Republican, argued against paying the defense costs. `` We did n't start this process; the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> did n't start this process'' when it impeached <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mawhinney </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, the governor, started the process.'' <PERSON> Mawhinney </PERSON> said that if senators wanted to show compassion they might want to pay the legal fees themselves, adding, `` I ca n't believe you can do that with somebody else's money. Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Chuy </PERSON> <PERSON> Higuera </PERSON> suggested that the state and <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> split the cost. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted Monday to remove <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, a first-term Republican, from office for obstructing justice by trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat and for misusing $ 80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. GOP Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> said he thought the matter should be referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and suggested that the $ 92,000 governor's protocol fund _ which remains in a bank _ might be used to pay <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s expenses <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said he expected to be paid whether the money came from the state or <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> himself. The attorney said that when he met with <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> after his conviction, `` I found not one sign of retribution in him of any thought of revenge or rancor.'' `` He said to us that when your first vote was completed ... that he felt relieved,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said. The prosecution took no position on whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s fees should be paid. Prosecutor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckstein </PERSON> said the matter should be up to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s discretion.
