<FIRST>r w AM-SavingsInstitutions     04-06 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savings Institutions,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Deposits Up for Fifth Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Deposits at federally insured savings institutions grew for the fifth consecutive month in February, continuing a trend begun after the October stock market crash, the government said Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates 3,126 savings institutions, said net deposits increased by $ 5.2 billion, compared with a $ 5.4 billion increase in January and a $ 1.1 billion net withdrawal in February 1987. The increase came despite the deteriorating financial condition of many thrift institutions, particularly in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> where institutions have been hit hard by the depressed energy and real estate markets. A third of the industry lost money last year, pushing overall 1987 losses to a post-Depression record of $ 6.8 billion. Despite the losses, money has been flowing into S & amp; L accounts, which are insured up to $ 100,000, since the crash: $ 6.2 billion in October, $ 3.2 billion in November, and $ 2.6 billion in December. That is reversing what was described as a slow-motion run on <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls, which had net withdrawals in seven of the first nine months of last year. `` I think you're still getting, as late as it seems, a kind of stock market effect here,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Obrinsky </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, the industry's largest trade group. `` Although the stock market has n't declined since October, it has n't gone up much either. A lot of consumers are rethinking what they're doing with their money and parking some or all of it into thrifts and perhaps banks,'' he said. Unlike the early months after the crash, which saw an increase in deposits of $ 100,000 and more, the increase so far in 1988 has come in smaller accounts, which are institutions' least costly source of funds. Meanwhile, in a separate report, the bank board said interest rates for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages fell from 10.48 percent in early February to 10.34 percent in early March, the lowest since last April. Rates on the most popular type of one-year adjustable mortgages, those with caps on how much the rate can change, fell less sharply, from 8.72 percent to 8.65 percent. The bank board figures do not reflect the most recent nudge upward in interest rates. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages have edged up from 9.84 percent on Feb. 12, the low for this year, to 10.05 percent on April 1. This survey did not include add-on fees, known as points, which are included in the bank board averages. Mortgage lending by S & amp; Ls rose slightly to $ 13.5 billion in February from $ 13.1 billion in January, which was the lowest level since February 1985, the bank board said.
