ack in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is examining the pros and cons of invoking IEEPA, and if it is a sensible thing to do to continue to apply pressure on General <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, then we will provide that to the president for his consideration.'' A senior administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it may not be possible to persuade <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses to withhold the tax payments voluntarily. He said some businesses `` are having difficulty because of their need to operate in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and because of what they believe are their legal obligations.'' This official also said that invoking the emergency powers law could damage the Panamanian economy beyond recovery in any post-Noriega era, saying `` we might regret it several months from now.'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said they had no evidence to back up a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> report Tuesday saying that an international Marxist brigade of up to 1,200 troops had been sent into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> late last month to protect <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` There are indications that there have been some <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> arms that have been flown into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in recent weeks, but I have no information supporting the presence of an international brigade,'' said <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>.
