<SECOND>AM-Friends Hospital, Bjt,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Hospital Celebrates 175 Years As Facility for Mentally Ill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Quakers who founded Friends Hospital 175 years ago chose a site on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> so the mentally ill could live and work in freedom from prying eyes and barred windows. That was part of the philosophy the Quakers, led by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scattergood </PERSON>, believed in when they opened the `` Asylum for Persons Deprived of the Use of their Reason.'' The institution is observing its anniversary this week. The `` moral treatment'' of the mentally ill was considered revolutionary at a time when the insane were put in chains in basements or on display for public amusement. `` Today, about every institution espouses ` moral treatment','' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelius </PERSON>, the hospital's coordinator of community relations. `` It was something that was accepted much more widely after Friends opened.'' The hospital was the first institution in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> exclusively for the mentally ill which was not under government auspices. Believing that `` there's that of God in every person,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Quakers </ORGANIZATION>' treatment included giving each patients as much responsibility as possiblee and and giving each an occupation to increase self-esteem. `` Just because you're sick does n't mean you're useless,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON>, today's director of the facility. The second non-Quaker director of the 11 who have served the hospital, <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON> said 70 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> members are <ORGANIZATION> Quakers </ORGANIZATION>, according to bylaws. `` It was set up to be Society of Friends dominated to assure the philosophy and principles were adhered to,'' he explained. <PERSON> Scattergood </PERSON> founded the hospital after visiting the Retreat at <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, a hospital for the mentally ill founded by <PERSON> Quaker </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuke </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scattergood </PERSON> quite likely was a depressant himself,'' <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON> said, noting descriptions of him as a `` melancholiac person.'' The original building, built in 1817 and used as administrative offices now, gave each patient a room of his own with a window. Ms. <PERSON> Kelius </PERSON> said planners for the building included a committee on light and air. That tradition continues. Each patient has his or her own room, though the bathroom is shared with one other patient. In 175 years, the hospital has added several buildings. The <ORGANIZATION> Greystone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, once the director's residence, houses 13 patients with long-term psychiatric illness in a program to teach daily living skills. At the turn of the century, the Hygeia Building was constructed for hydrotherapy, a treatment similar to a whirlpool with the person wrapped in a towel-like material, according to <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON>. Treatments that once included purging, bloodletting and spinning a patient while seated in a chair were used at Friends Hospital, but have been discarded. `` The medical approach ... changes with the vogue in medicine,'' <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON> said. `` The moral treatment has not changed.'' Patients have two hours daily of activity therapy which may include occupational or recreational therapy, creative arts and horticulture. The first year, <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> had 19 patients. In 1982, the hospital expanded to 192 beds. Now, a day program with 24 people allows patients to undergo the same treatment as regular patients, but leave the hospital at night. At first, the Quakers only wanted to admit patients of their faith and people who had not been ill for an extended period of time. After finding that there were not enough patients to fill beds, they opened up the facility to all faiths and long-term illnesses. The 100-acre site of <LOCATION> Friends </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in north <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> is no longer rural, but the hospital is still surrounded by open areas, trees and gardens. `` With the development of the surrounding area, we've always had a buffer,'' <PERSON> Delaplane </PERSON> explained. `` The fact of the open space has been a community asset.''
