<HEAD>Reagan Remark on Pardons Called Merely ``Throwaway Comment''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was giving merely a `` throwaway comment'' when he made a remark interpreted by some congressmen as a sign he might pardon former aides <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. `` I do n't think it's safe to make any conclusions about the president's attitude about pardons,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vacationed at his mountaintop ranch. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> confirmed that the president, at a closed meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on March 22, had been urged by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., to pardon <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, who have been indicted on felony charges in the Iran-Contra affair <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> suggested <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sign pardons in the final days of his term next January, possibly in a ceremony at the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> Veterans Memorial in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>'s comments were greeted by applause from other <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> congressmen. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` I like the sound of those words,'' according to one unidentified congressman quoted by The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. Another lawmaker recalled the president as saying, `` I like hearing what you said.'' Some lawmakers have taken <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comment as a hint that he will pardon the two former national security aides, but <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> played down the significance of the remarks. He said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` told them he was not discussing pardons, period, and then he had some throwaway line which was similar'' to the remark quoted by the congressmen. `` I gave them no significance at the time. I do n't give them any significance now. Certainly you've heard the president say much stronger things than that in terms of his feelings about <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>,'' the spokesman said. He added, `` I do n't believe you should make any assumptions or conclusions on the basis of that throwaway comment.'' Emphasizing his point, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` It's been three weeks -LRB- since <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comment -RRB-. There could n't have been too much _ you'd have had 40 congressmen running out of the room, grabbing the cameras like you ca n't believe. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` I have raised the issue -LRB- of pardons -RRB- with the president four or five times myself and I've heard it raised by others, and every time the president says the same thing: ` I'm not discussing pardons.''' However, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has made several comments that have fueled speculation about pardons. Answering a question from a student last month, he expressed the conviction that <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> `` are going to be found innocent, because I do n't think they were guilty of any lawbreaking or any crime.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` I still think <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> is a hero.'' Days later, he qualified his remark about heroism, saying he was referring to combat honors North had won in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has said the president `` is committed to seeing that the legal system operates. And I do not anticipate that he'll address the pardon issue until it does.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> declined to interpret what <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> meant about seeing the legal system operate. `` I do n't know,'' he said. `` I've not heard the president say that.'' North and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, along with arms dealers <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, have pleaded innocent to federal criminal charges in the sale of arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the diversion of money to Contra rebels fighting the leftist government of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
