<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who is cautiously expanding contacts with some of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s staunchest allies, will hold talks with the highest-ranking East German and communist Bulgarian to visit <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, officials said Wednesday. <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Axen </PERSON>, a member of the ruling East German politburo, will meet <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> on May 3 during a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and East German sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the meeting was arranged after <PERSON> Axen </PERSON> was invited to give a lecture at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contemporary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> on May 4. Although <PERSON> Axen </PERSON> holds no office in the East German government, he is the top international affairs officer of the communist <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which controls government policy. <PERSON> Andrey </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukanov </PERSON>, Bulgarian minister for foreign economic development, will meet <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> during an April 25-26 visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lukanov </PERSON>, a former deputy premier whose post was created in a recent government reorganization, will be the first Bulgarian cabinet minister to visit <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> since World War II. Since 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has gingerly increased its overtures to Soviet bloc countries, not with great hopes of wooing them from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s domination but to chip away wherever possible at hard-line human rights and economic policies. In visits over the past two years, Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> has told leaders in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> eagerness to expand commercial ties will depend on their willingness to improve human rights conditions. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> source said that during <PERSON> Axen </PERSON>'s talks, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials will renew pleas for better human rights performance, notably in the realm of religion. In what the official described as a `` mixed bag'' of actions, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last year allowed two massive religious assemblies, and the East German Jewish community was allowed to install its first rabbi since 1967. In recent weeks, however, there has been a crackdown on environmental groups affiliated with churches, the official said. Axen and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also will discuss the two countries' effort to settle financial claims by Americans whose property on East German territory was taken during and after World War II. The claims total more than $ 70 million. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort to get other countries to do more to stop terrorism and the flow of drugs is another likely topic, the official said. An East German diplomat said `` the main intention of these talks will be to promote the relationship between both countries and contribute to a further buildup of the relationship.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and East German officials said they doubted there would be serious talk about a visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by East German leader <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON>, as was reported in a West German magazine. <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> is known to be interested in such a visit `` but it is n't ripe for discussion,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said In talks with the Bulgarian official, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is expected to reassert requests for better human rights policies, notably toward <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s sizable Turkish and <PERSON> Islamic </PERSON> minority. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> wants to expand trade with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> beyond the current $ 130 million level. Before he leaves the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on May 2, <PERSON> Lukanov </PERSON> is expected to call for improved commercial ties during talks at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and in meetings in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
