<HEAD>Age-60 Limit for Pilots Must Be Justified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> must justify to a jury its requirement that test and training pilots stop flying at age 60 and ca n't rely on a similar limit for commercial pilots, a federal appeals court ruled Wednesday. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated an age discrimination suit by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission against the Seattle-based aircraft company. According to the court, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has 41 pilots who train other pilots and 24 who make test flights. The company set its age-60 limit in 1980, forcing some pilots into layoffs or early retirement, the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> dismissed the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> suit, citing the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s longstanding rule requiring pilots of large commercial passenger planes to stop flying at 60. She said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rule was based on safety concerns that applied equally to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court said a jury must decide on the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>'s claim that it would be practical to examine pilots over 60 for disabilities, rather than automatically disqualifying them. Under federal law, the court said, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> must prove that individual testing is impractical. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rule applies only to certain commercial pilots, and the agency has expressly refused to apply the rule to other types of piliots, said Chief Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> in the 3-0 decision. `` It may be that the age-60 rule reflects an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> decision to resolve any doubts about the necessity for an age qualification in favor of the substantial number of passengers carried by -LRB- the airlines covered by the rule -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> said. He said a court can not assume that the same considerations would make an age-60 limit a business necessity for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, who is 69 and recently announced his intention to step down as chief judge but remain an active member of the court, said Judge <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> did not consider <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> evidence of new scientific testing methods accurately predicting individual loss of function. He said <PERSON> Rothstein </PERSON> also disregarded evidence that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employed pilots over 60 without incident before 1980, that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had rescinded its age-60 limit for pilots, and that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and airlines have used elaborate testing procedures to allow pilots to resume flying after being grounded for alcoholism or heart disease. There was also evidence that some of the work done by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> pilots, such as flight training, was less stressful and dangerous than the jobs of commercial pilots, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> said.
