 When officer W.E. <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> gives out speeding tickets, he sends drivers on their way with, `` Have a nice day.'' Some apparentlydo, and they send <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> fan mail in return. `` I want to treat people the way I would want to be treated in the same circumstance,'' said <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, who writes about 125 tickets a month and has received about 10 fan letters this year from motorists caught speeding on the congested streets of this <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> suburb. `` He pulled me over and was as nice as he could be. Most policemen today seem to be on a power trip or ego trip,'' said <LOCATION> Acworth </LOCATION> resident <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillebeau </PERSON>, who got a ticket for traveling 47 mph in a 30 mph zone. `` He was so different from the rest that I wanted to commend him on his good attitude.'' Not all motorists are fans, however. One driver kicked out his own taillights and dented his car while <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> was writing the ticket. `` I almost had to arrest him,'' <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> said.
