<HEAD>Fate of Afghan Leaders Uncertain After Troop Withdrawal, Soviet
Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading Soviet expert on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> said Wednesday that the pro-Kremlin regime in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> may survive the withdrawal of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> but that the lives of its leaders `` are in the hands of the almighty.'' In a remarkably pessimistic public assessment for a Soviet, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime controls about 30 percent of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, including most administrative centers, that tribal leaders control about 30 percent, and that the Islamic guerrillas known as mujahedeen control just over 30 percent. The complicated balance of power hampers predictions of what will happen when and if the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> pulls out, said <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON>. Although some guerrillas have close ties with the fundamentalist Moslem government in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> said, `` my impression is that an Islamic republic in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is impossible'' because tribal leaders are so strong. Many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> analysts believe that the pro-Kremlin government will collapse immediately after a Soviet pullout, and that regime officials who do not leave will be targets of revenge from the families of the estimated 1 million Afghans who were killed or the 5 million Afghans driven into exile during the war. `` Individual acts of revenge may take place,'' <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> said. `` But I hope that a blood bath will not take place.'' `` It is impossible to predict the future of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>,'' the leader of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime, he said. `` But we have the impression that the regime of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZ