f Soviet troops even if the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> talks collapse. Under the Soviet system, experts such as <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> not only write scholarly works but are asked to prepare classified reports for the key decision-making body on foreign relations, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> secretariat. <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> declined to say what advice he has the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> about <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, explaining that `` a lecture is not a confessional.'' He denied that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> plans to annex any part of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. And he avoided direct comment on speculation that Soviet withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> signalled an end to the so-called `` Brezhnev Doctrine,'' invoked in the past to justify military intervention to prop up communist regimes in such nations such as <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Instead, <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON> clamed that <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> never had a communist government. Although <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his colleagues represent a leftist faction within the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Gankovsky </PERSON>, `` there are not any communists'' among them. `` The biggest part of them are Afghan nationalists. They are not communists, they are not socialists,'' he said, drawing a fine line which was challenged vocally by some Afghan emigres in the audience. The chances that a pro-Kremlin regime would prevail in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> are bolstered by the high rate of party membership, 75 percent, among military and police officials, and by the large number of Afghans, 400,000, employed by the state, he said.
