Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, have unseated their incumbent mayor, <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> voters have elected their first new mayor in 28 years and the mayor of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, survived a recall election provoked by racial tension. Elsewhere, a campaign supported by presidential candidate <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> succeeded in defeating a <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> charter amendment that was viewed as an attack on the city's highest elected black. <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> Mayor-elect <PERSON> Rodger </PERSON> <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> said Wednesday he will spend the first 100 days in office balancing next year's city budget, preparing a charter change proposal and making a blueprint for economic development for his once oil-rich city. The budget is expected to fall $ 6 million short next year. <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> said he also intends to propose a change in the city's charter, which has been challenged by the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> as being unfair to blacks The National Association for the <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> filed suit claiming the city's commission form of government dilutes black voting strength. <PERSON> Randle </PERSON>, 44, soundly defeated Republican <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, 54, in Tuesday's election, claiming 55.3 percent or 45,517 votes to <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>'s 34.2 percent or 28,142 votes. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, elected in 1986, said he looks forward to spending more time with his family, getting back into banking and refusing to talk to reporters who once called at all hours. In <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> swept to victory over former acting Gov. <PERSON> Martin </P