<FIRST>r a AM-Sunspots     04-06 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sunspots,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Sunspot Theory Bolstered By Early Detection Of Solar Jet
Streams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A theory that upsets traditional notions about 11-year sunspot cycles has been bolstered by the earliest, most detailed observation ever made of solar jet streams that will produce sunspots by 1997, scientists say. Astronomer <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> and his colleagues at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, were able to see the jet streams `` at higher latitudes -LRB- on the sun -RRB- and earlier than we were ever able to before,'' said astrophysicist <PERSON> Herschel </PERSON> <PERSON> Snodgrass </PERSON> of <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION> `` We're seeing the very earliest stage of the next sunspot cycle, not the one that is producing sunspots now, but that one that will produce them when this cycle is over,'' said <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON>, who presented his findings Wednesday during a solar physics meeting in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Understanding the sunspot cycle is important because the spots and related explosions called solar flares disrupt radar, radio and other communications on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and, in extreme cases, are believed to contribute to ice ages and major droughts, <PERSON> Snodgrass </PERSON> said Tuesday by telephone from <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> said solar flares make <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s outer atmosphere expand, so learning more about sunspots is important in deciding when to launch satellites, since atmospheric expansion produces orbit-altering drag on spacecraft. <PERSON> Snodgrass </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> astrophysicist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Altrock </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON>'s observation of the jet streams, which are east-west currents of gas parallel to the sun's equator, supports a theory they developed independently with <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> astronomer <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. Last year, they proposed that the 11-year sunspot cycle _ during which the number of sunspots reaches a maximum, then a minimum and then another maximum _ is merely part of a previously unknown 18-to 22-year cycle that produces visible sunspots only during its last 11 years. The theory says that during the earliest stages of this longer cycle, jet stream-like gas currents appear near the sun's poles like smoke rings, which then grow and roll down the sun toward the equator, <PERSON> Altrock </PERSON> said by telephone from <LOCATION> Sunspot </LOCATION>, N.M. Only when the jet streams reach a solar latitude of 30 or 35 degrees do they produce sunspots, <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> said. He said he detected the jet streams at a latitude of 70 degrees on the sun. `` These jet streams eventually will migrate into the region where sunspots form,'' probably about 1997, <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> said. The last sunspot cycle reached its minimum in September 1986, so the next maximum is expected about 1991 and the next minimum in 1997 or 1998, <PERSON> Snodgrass </PERSON> said. The current batch of sunspots `` is rising much faster than any other we've seen,'' he added. `` There is evidence to suggest it's going to be unusually strong and perhaps the maximum will be reached earlier than usual, in 1989 or 1990,'' with the minimum following in 1995 or 1996 Sunspots are relatively cool spots, 1,200 to 60,000 miles across, that each appear for three to seven weeks where the solar magnetic field is about 1,000 times stronger than in other locations. Up to 30 appear at one time. <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> and his colleagues were able to see the solar jet streams closer to the sun's poles in more detail than ever before by measuring the speed of gases on the sun's surface 20 times daily using the 150-foot-tall solar observatory and 75-foot-deep spectrograph on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wilson </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gabriel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> northeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Sunlight passes through a lens near the top of the observatory tower. The lens focuses an image of the sun on a hole that lets the light enter the spectrograph. The spectrograph breaks the sunlight into a rainbow of component colors. That allows the scientists to measure the speed of solar gases and detect jet streams. `` It's the same way a radar gun on the highway measures the velocity of a car,'' <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> said. The jet streams may help scientists understand why the number of sunspots varies, <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
