<HEAD>Arms Treaty Will Save Pentagon $1.7 Billion, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Destruction of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> medium-range missiles under the new U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms reduction treaty will save the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> about $ 1.7 billion through the fall of 1995, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. The savings will come because the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> will no longer need to maintain its Pershing and ground-launched cruise missile force in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Money will also be saved on associated costs for military personnel, procurement, and construction of housing for military family members, it said. `` Army officials told us that some of the equipment procured under the Pershing II program would not be subject to treaty limitation and would therefore be available for use in other <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units,'' the GA0 said. It said this includes radios, trucks, generators, tool kits and other support equipment whose total value is unclear. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, it said, has identified more than $ 550 million in equipment that will be reused and about $ 50 million in funding that will be recovered because of project cancellations. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> quoted <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials as saying that 76 launch control centers, valued at about $ 6 million each for a total $ 456 million, will be reused. And it said about $ 114 million worth of missile components produced under existing <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> contracts will be made available to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> for its sea-launched cruise missile program. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> also expects to recover about $ 40 million to $ 58 million in previously approved military construction funds, according to the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. The treaty would require the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to destroy a total of 867 medium-range missiles while the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would be required to eliminate some 1,800 weapons. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missiles to be destroyed over a 36-month period beginning after the pact is ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, include 178 Pershing IAs, 247 Pershing IIs, and 442 ground-launched cruise missiles, together with their launchers and certain support and training equipment. The costs of actually destroying the weapons are classified and will be provided separately to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the agency said. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spent a total $ 6.5 billion for the Pershing II and ground-launched cruise missile systems, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, including $ 2.6 billion for the Pershings and $ 3.45 billion for the cruise missiles. Those totals include the costs of research and development, procurement, military construction and missile modifications. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 17-2 last month to recommend the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approve the treaty. Barring unexpected developments, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate on the treaty is expected to begin late this month or in early May. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report was requested by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, an opponent of the treaty.
