<FIRST>r a AM-HensonBurial     04-06 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Henson Burial,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains of Black Co-Discoverer of North Pole Buried in Arlington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The black co-discoverer of the North Pole received what one supporter called `` long overdue recognition'' as his remains were reinterred with full military honors Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> was the first to reach the North Pole and planted the American flag there exactly 79 years earlier during a trek with Adm. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> and four Eskimos. <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> was buried at <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> in 1920 and a huge monument to him was erected by his grave. <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>, however, ended up at his death in 1955 in a shared grave at <LOCATION> Woodlawn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> because his wife could not afford a separate gravesite. `` He was denied proper recognition because of the racial attitudes of his time,'' said Dr. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Counter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professor who successfully petitioned President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to allow <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s reinterment at <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>. Counter, who previously had brought together <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s part-Eskimo offspring, told about 100 relatives and admirers at the windswept hilltop burial site that the reinterment of <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>, was `` long overdue recognition for our hero ... -LRB- that would -RRB- right a tragic wrong.'' `` Welcome home, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>,'' he said. `` Welcome home to a new day in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. ... May your presence here inspire generations of explorers.'' <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s remains now rest alongside <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s, with the remains of their wives on either side. Descendants of <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> were joined at the ceremony by <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s part-Eskimo descendants fathered when he was in the Arctic. `` Now, finally, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Peary </PERSON> can talk about old days out there,'' a grandson, <PERSON> Qitdlaq </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Qaanaaq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, said through a translator at a news conference following the ceremony. A monument installed next to the gravesite includes a quote from <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>, who was 88 when he died: `` The lure of the Arctic is tugging at my heart. To me the trail is calling! The old trail _ The trail that is always new.'' Although repeated references were made to <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s concern that <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s achievements be recognized, none of <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s relatives attended the ceremony, <PERSON> Counter </PERSON> said. `` I'm sorry they're not here,'' <PERSON> Counter </PERSON> said at the news conference, adding that he had invited both <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s son and grandson and had offered to help with travel arrangements. He said that if he had known none of <PERSON> Peary </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> descendants were going to attend, he would have invited his part-Eskimo offspring. Counter said the costs of the reinterments _ including exhuming the <ORGANIZATION> Hensons </ORGANIZATION> from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> cemetery, the two bronze caskets, the monument, bringing <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>'s offspring from <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and the rest of the arrangements _ ran into the thousands, but he would not be more specific or say