<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge Ready To Set Trial Dates for North, Poindexter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf bgng: Under the ... to CORRECT term to `special
compartmented' sted `secure compartmented; SUBS 7th graf bgng:
Walsh said ... to include prosecution's estimate of timing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra case signaled Wednesday he was ready to discuss a `` realistic trial date'' to achieve an `` expeditious disposition'' of the criminal charges against the four defendants. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> rejected as too cumbersome a proposal by independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> for elaborate procedures to prevent the unauthorized disclosure of 150,000 pages of classified documents that may become evidence in the case. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal `` appears to be far too complex, lacks definite time restrictions and creates undue obstacles to the fair and expeditous disposition of this case,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said in a brief opinion. Under the prosecution plan, defense lawyers for former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and arms dealers <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> would be required to obtain security clearances before they could examine the documents at a `` special compartmented information facility.'' The four defendants are accused of conspiring to defraud the government by diverting some of the profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s propposal laid out intricate steps under the Classified Information Procedures Act for court review of sensitive documents that might be introduced by either side as evidence when the case goes to trial. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said defense lawyers can not begin examining the documents until adequate procedures are imposed by the court. He said pre-trial discovery could take three months. But <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said `` it will be necessary to frame a more limited protective order fashioned to the nature of this case, which in essence alleges a course of conduct carried out using classified materials in classified channels from a highly classified site.'' The judge said he wants to determine `` to what extent'' the documents `` will be made available available immediately'' for inspection by the defense. At a hearing scheduled for next Tuesday, `` the court intends to determine the timing of discovery disclosures in relation to a realistic trial date,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he wants to set an April deadline for interagency review of the classified materials that have been collected during <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s 15-month investigation and set a time for the defense to notify the court if it intends to use any secret documents as evidence. Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, the defense is required to tell the court which material it will use. The statute contains procedures for the court to review the documents to determine which, if any, are relevant to the proceedings. The judge has the power to delete certain secret material and substitute statements of facts a particular document would prove. The so-called `` graymail'' statute was enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 to facilitate prosecution of espionage cases and to control the disclosure of classified information at trial. The procedures were envisioned to balance secrecy with the government's need to use classified documents as evidence. Representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> are reviewing the documents assembled by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to determine if any can be declassified. In his pleadings, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said the documents `` describe in detail some of the nation's most carefully held secrets about its foreign policy, its intelligence activities and its covert activities.'' The defendants filed a joint opposition to <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s motion for expedited consideration of the proposed protective order, noting that North and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> had access to many of the documents when they were at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The defense motion said <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s proposal raised a number of issues about the constitutionality of the classified information law as well as the independent counsel's power to represent the government's national security interests.
