<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with interview, review of day's activities</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinians who renounce terror and recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> are welcome at <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace talks, but not the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> or those `` who have committed acts of terrorism,'' Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> spoke in an interview that was televised in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as he met with King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. It was taped in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> earlier Wednesday. The secretary, who called <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> `` a man of peace,'' hopes to persuade the king and Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to drop their reservations and agree to negotations. `` Say yes to this initiative,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> implored <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> in a statement after a final meeting with the prime minister Wednesday. `` Let us redouble our efforts to make it -LRB- peace -RRB- a reality.'' As he passed the halfway point in his latest <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> venture, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> acknowledged having little to show for his second visit to the region in a month. He said he was still committed to making the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace plan work, but declared: `` In all candor, I am not able to say that it is happening. While we have made some progress, differences have not been substantially narrowed.'' On departure from <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurion </PERSON> airport, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> pledged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its security, but said in apparent criticism of <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s reluctance: `` More fundamentally, security and progress for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> comes from peace between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its neighbors. It is p