<BYLINE>By PAIGE ST. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A veterans' group Wednesday agreed to admit `` anyone presenting a ticket'' to an oyster dinner it has held for men only for 39 years but said this is the last year it will conduct the event. `` Men have a right to have a stag party,'' the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> chapter of the Forty & amp; <PERSON> Eight </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasociete </PERSON> said in a statement. `` This has always been a classy affair sponsored by a classy organization. We are not pigs and neither are we backward.'' The dinner, expected to attract 1,200 people Friday, is a favorite campaign stop for candidates. But Republican congressional candidate <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> said she had been told she would not be admitted because she is a woman, even though she bought a ticket. Other candidates subsequently said they would not show up unless women were allowed. Attorney General <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, also seeking re-election this year, entered the fray Tuesday with a letter to <ORGANIZATION> McDowell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> school Superintendent <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> pointing out that the dinner site, a high school in the county, is public property and anyone with a ticket must be allowed to attend. `` We all would agree <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> needed progressive changes,'' <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` This is one giant step in that direction.'' The Forty & amp; Eight chapter said no one will be allowed into the event without a ticket, no tickets will be sold at the door and it will discontinue the dinners, its only fund-raising event, after this year. `` It is unfortunate that outsiders who could have directed attention to the event and what results from it instead chose to enhance their own welfare,'' the organization said. `` They should have been making statements about the good things that result from the event.'' Money from the $ 15-a-ticket dinner goes toward sponsorship of groups such as the Little League and Special Olympics, the statement said. Forty & amp; Eight, based nationally in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, began as an honorary society for American Legion members, but the groups are now separate and Legion officials in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> dissociated themselves from the stag affair. `` We split in 1972. We do n't even allow Forty & amp; Eight lapel pins on people in our parades, that's how much we split,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vass </PERSON>, state adjutant for the Legion. `` It's just a redneck approach,'' he said of the stag dinner. `` This is 1988! You do n't disenfranchise a congressional candidate because she's a woman.''
