<HEAD>Famine-Plagued Regions Too Dangerous For Relief Workers,
Government Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Wednesday advised international relief agencies to remove their foreign workers from two drought-stricken northern regions because of increasing rebel violence. The government's <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> regions no longer are safe for the foreign agencies. `` In recent weeks the emergency relief aid distribution by the -LRB- commission -RRB- and international donor organizations has been disrupted by terrorists engaged in destructive activities against the unity, integrity and freedom of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>,'' the commission said in a two-page statement distributed to foreign aid groups. `` In addition to the destruction of trucks flying the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> flag and transportation of relief supplies, the bandits have time and again kidnapped expatriates in the regions,'' it said. The commission said foreigners should stay out of the north `` until the areas are freed from terrorist activity and tranquility is restored to the life of the civilian population in the areas.'' The government agency asked donors and international relief agencies to turn over their operations to the commission to guarantee the continuity of aid to the starving. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s food crisis is becoming more severe because there is not enough security for aid workers. `` We're naturally concerned that any diminution of the international relief effort will have a negative impact on the lives of starving people,'' she said. `` Clearly, in an unpredictable war situation, safety for relief personnel is also a serious consideration,'' she said. `` We hope that the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> government will take steps to ensure the safety of relief personnel as well.'' Last week, President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> told Ethiopians in a radio address that government troops were facing a `` grim struggle'' against separatist rebels in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said the government was mobilizing troops to crush the rebellions. Separatist rebels have been fighting for 27 years in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and 14 years in <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>. The fighting has disrupted relief efforts in both regions, where crop failures threaten 3.5 million people with starvation. Overall, nearly 7 million Ethiopians are facing famine. There are about 60 non-governmental relief organizations working in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, but only a few operate in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tigray </LOCATION>. Agencies operating in the area include the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, Doctors Without Borders of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the relief agencies in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> arrived during a 1984-85 drought and famine that killed an estimated 1 million Ethiopians. It prompted the biggest aid effort in history. Most foreign agencies pared their expatriate staffs after the 1984-85 emergency and turned over programs to Ethiopians. Exact numbers of foreign workers still in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> were not immediately available.
