<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> informed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday that he has stripped <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> of certain fishing rights because of that country's alleged violation of an international whale conservation program. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had certified the violations based on permits <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has issued for the killing of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION> minke whales for research purposes. `` The sanctions are the strongest possible'' under legislation authorizing presidential action, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. The administration maintains that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has run afoul of an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whaling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> whale conservation program by issuing permits for research that has never been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> IWC </ORGANIZATION>. The issuance of the permits by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to its citizens came despite a 1987 whaling commission resolution recommending that no such licenses be granted until questions about the research program were resolved, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s letter said. It noted that shortly after the certification of the violations by <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON>, the whaling commission adopted a second resolution recommending that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> not go ahead with its research program. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has continued its whaling activities notwithstanding this second resolution,'' the letter said. Under provisions of the Magnuson Fishery Conservation and Management Act and the Fishermen's Protective Act, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> directed the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to withhold 100 percent of the fishing privileges `` that would otherwise be available to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' in waters under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authority. The current Japanese fishing quota in the 200-mile offshore <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic zone is zero. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he was denying <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s request to fish for 3,000 metric tons of sea snails and 5,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> whiting. `` In addition, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will be barred from any future allocations of fishing privileges for any other species, including <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> cod, until the secretary of commerce determines that the situation has been corrected,'' he said. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> affiliate of the World Wildlife Fund, said the announced fishing sanctions `` would hurt some,'' but came too late to save any of the 300 minke whales <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to take in this year's research program. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s letter to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said that `` the immediate and prospective effects of a 100 percent reduction of fishing allocations, coupled with presidential review in the near future, is the most effective means of encouraging <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to embrace the <ORGANIZATION> IWC </ORGANIZATION> conservation program.'' `` Therefore, I will not impose at this time'' any sanctions against Japanese fish products imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to report by Dec. 1 on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s willingness to comply with the whaling conservation program. He also said he was directing <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to continue talks with whaling commission member countries `` to ensure that we bring to a halt all whaling that diminishes the effectiveness of the <ORGANIZATION> IWC </ORGANIZATION>'s conservation program.'' `` Our actions taken today and in the future should encourage all nations to adhere to the conservation programs of the <ORGANIZATION> IWC </ORGANIZATION>,'' the president's letter said.
