<TEXT>
 A two-man <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team will leave for <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> on Thursday to investigate <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s charges that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has used chemical weapons, spokesman <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said Wednesday. The same team went to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> last week to look into Iranian charges that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used gas bombs last month that killed 5,000 people, but no report has been released. The <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> neighbors have been at war since September 1980. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was angered by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team's visit to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. It accused the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> of siding with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and asked Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, for whom <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> speaks, to conduct a similar investigation of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s tactics. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio quoted Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> as saying the decision to send the team to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was `` surprising'' and he had written to <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to complain. The secretary-general has said there was evidence that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used chemical weapons and appealed to both sides to stop attacking civilian targets. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> met Wednesday with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Javad </PERSON> <PERSON> Larijani </PERSON>, and is to meet next week with <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> foreign