iscussed,'' Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacayo </PERSON>, chief of the Sandinista delegation, said in a broadcast interview after discussions recessed for the day. <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> is chief of staff of the Sandinista army. The Contras are to gather in the zones during the first 15 days of April. It still must be decided how to provide security assurances for the rebels and how humanitarian assistance can be delivered to them. On March 23, the two sides formally agreed to the truce as part of a plan to end a war that killed or wounded an estimated 50,000 people over nearly seven years. Neither the leftist Sandinista government nor the Nicaraguan Resistance, the U.S.-supported Contra rebel organization, says it is satisfied with the other side's compliance with the accord. Contra leaders accused the Sandinistas of violating a section of the pact that calls for `` unrestricted freedom of expression'' by failing to supply newsprint to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s only opposition newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>. At a news conference Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> publisher <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> called the newsprint restriction `` a deliberate blow to freedom of expression in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The accord also called for the release of 100 political prisoners on March 27. The Contras complain the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> freed only 10 of the prisoners the rebels had on their list, although the pact does not specify the rebels have a say in who goes free. Issues still pending include how and when the Contras will lay down their weapons. This is not spelled out in the plan, nor does the plan say what will happen to the Contras after they gather in the zones. Under the plan, the government pledges `` that the individuals who have been reintegrated into normal civilian life will be able to take part in future elections.'' But `` normal civilian life'' is open to interpretation in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, where the government claims to have 300,000 people under arms. The Contras backed out of a high-level meeting `` to continue definitive cease-fire negotiations,'' originally set for Wednesday in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the capital. They said the meeting must wait until security issues for the rebels were resolved. The two sides are arguing about an agenda for the next meeting, as well as a date. In addition, the Contras insist that their 55-member delegation stay at <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>'s downtown Intercontinental Hotel and be free to meet with political opposition leaders. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Zambrana </PERSON>, head of reservations at the hotel, said Wednesday the Contras have reserved 50 rooms for April 12-15. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have said that for security reasons the <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> delegation would be housed at a hotel near the airport.
