contracts and updated value.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> hired at least one company linked to earlier drug smuggling to transport aid to the U.S.-backed Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, and was put in touch with the company by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, according to congressional testimony and sources. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanitarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in early 1986 signed a series of contracts totaling more than $ 300,000 with Vortex, a small <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> air transport and service company, to airlift `` humanitarian'' aid to the rebels, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, an admitted former drug pilot who then worked for Vortex, said Wednesday. The company was unprepared to handle the volume of supplies the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> wanted transported and had to rent a larger warehouse to accommodate the job, <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations narcotics subcommittee. Vortex also did airplane maintenance work for <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> proprietary companies resupplying the Contras in 1987, and in late 1986 sold the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> supply operation a DC-6 that formerly had been used to haul drugs, according to his testimony and committee staff members. Investigators for the congressional Iran-Contra committees have told the narcotics panel that the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> selected Vortex from a list of transport companies provided by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee source, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` If the Contra delivery system is using known narcotics dealers -LRB- for airlifts -RRB-, it's no wonder you have confusion surrounding the policy,'' said subcommittee chairman Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass. It was unclear whether the department knew that it was hiring a company with drug links to undertake part of the resupply operation. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Duemling </PERSON>, who ran the <ORGANIZATION> NHAO </ORGANIZATION>, was expected to testify before the panel on Thursday. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said the arrangement illustrated `` the absurdity, not to mention the impropriety, of a government contract going to someone -LRB- with drug involvement -RRB-, handing out <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayer dollars to support their business.'' `` Something's wrong here,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said. `` A contractor to <ORGANIZATION> NHAO </ORGANIZATION>, flying in an ex-drug plane, working simultaneously in narcotics undercover and supplying goods to the Contras.'' But <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said that was part of the reality of drug enforcement efforts. He said agencies do n't have the money to own their own aircraft for undercover operations or the desire to undertake such risky ventures themselves. `` Enter sf a $ 27 million <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> effort to deliver non-lethal supplies to the Contras, authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> later sharply criticized the operation, saying large amounts of the aid could not be accounted for. Wednesday's hearing was part of a continuing series of sessions <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said are intended to alert the public and policymakers to the pervasiveness of drug trading throughout <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Later witnesses, <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said, will establish even stronger links between drug trafficking and resupply efforts for the Contras. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> was arrested on marijuana smuggling charges in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> in 1986 along with others, while working for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and acting at the same time as an informant for the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Others charged at that time were convicted, but <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>'s indictment was dropped because of his role in helping the government, he testified. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said the decision to drop charges against him was made locally, in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, and was due to circumstances surrounding an undercover operation, and did not involve <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> higher-ups or the Contra connection. But <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said there had been a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting about disposition of <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>'s case and that the question of who prompted his release remained open.
