<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An oversupply of doctors that is widely predicted for the turn of the century will not materialize, and there could be a shortage instead, two reports predict. The reports contradict an often-repeated prophesy that the nation will have tens of thousands too many physicians by the year 2000 and so should train fewer doctors. `` I see no basis for cutting back on the number of new physicians,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think we are likely to be in rough balance and could have even a modest shortage of physicians.''
