<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday April 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Temporary Relief From Tax Pressure, Take Form 4868</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Internal Revenue Service Form 4868 is surely a popular piece of paper right now. For those who have not yet had occasion to use it, 4868 is the document taxpayers must file by April 15 to get an automatic extension of the deadline on their federal tax returns. Such extensions are in heavy demand this year, with taxpayers and paid preparers struggling to adjust to the new system that went into effect in 1987 mandated by tax reform. Confusion has been running high about many provisions of the new code, even among professional veterans of the tax wars. Suppose, for example, that you have `` passive losses'' from some partnership activity. `` The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> recently released 265 pages of temporary passive loss regulations, and this is only the beginning,'' observed the <ORGANIZATION> J.K. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lasser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in its current monthly bulletin. If you are overwhelmed by tax questions, preoccupied by other pressing matters or simply in a mood to procrastinate, you can put off the deadline for completing your return until Aug. 15 by simply filing Form 4868 now. For this extension, unlike any subsequent one you might seek, the government does n't require any explanation or excuse. But if Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> has any money coming from you, he wants it now, not later. The rules require that you include with Form 4868 a check for the estimated balance of what you still owe, beyond what was withheld from your wages or salary and any other payments you have already made. The estimate should be made with some care. If it turns out that you still owe money for 1987 when you file your return on, say, June 30, the government will charge you interest at a 10 percent annual rate on the balance due. And if what you still owe amounts to more than 10 percent of your total tax bill for the year, a penalty may also be imposed. Although it is a helpful option to have, an extension is not always an unmixed blessing. For one thing, if you have a refund coming, you ca n't claim it with Form 4868. That has to wait until your return is filed. And in the interim the government has what amounts to the free use of the money. That cost may be a small one to pay, however, if an extension allows you or your professional preparer the breathing space necessary to make a careful computation of every tax break to which you are entitled. Extensions are also automatically granted, without a Form 4868, for two months if you can document that you were out of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> on April 15. But a quick dash across the border and back will no longer do the trick. Nettled by an airline's advertisements touting foreign travel as a tax dodge, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> recently said these extensions apply only to people who can show that they were out of the country for at least 14 consecutive days, including all of April 15. Does an extension in any form increase, or reduce, your chances of getting audited? Probably not, says the <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guide </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some tax experts contend that you should request the maximum extension allowed for filing your return, arguing that the chances of an audit are reduced since <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> field agents will have less time to conduct the audit,'' the accounting firm says. `` Other tax experts contend you're better off filing on April 15 since this way you get lost in the crowd. Both theories are oversimplifications of <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> procedures.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday April 7</NOTE>
