<HEAD>Mainline Denomination Abandoning Pro-Choice Abortion Stand</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mainline American denomination, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, is backing away from its support of abortion rights, officials indicated this week. It was the first such definitive shift projected among the larger, socially activist Protestant bodies. Similar reassessments have come in some other major denominations, either stiffening opposition to abortion, or qualifying acceptance of it. But some still take an essentially pro-choice position. The turn away from it planned by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptists </ORGANIZATION> stemmed both from simmering discontent with the past stance and the swelling tide of abortions in the country. `` The great proliferation of abortion has made us stop and look at what's happening here,'' says <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, head of a task force which has been re-examining the issue for more than two years. `` It's a process of reevaluation and reassessment,'' she said in a telephone interview. `` This is a continuing necessity if the church is to carry out its prophetic role on such a key social issue.'' She said positions ca n't be fixed `` in concrete,'' but `` are pulled along by social changes on the issue and as we understand more about it.'' She termed the projected new stand `` responsibility to choose life.'' It attempts a path-breaking middle ground. `` It is a pro-life stance in affirming the sacredness of life as a gift of God,'' she said. But it avoids both the `` pro-life'' and `` pro-choice'' terms commonly used in the polarized conflict over abortion. Mrs. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, a former missionary in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and wife of a minister, said: `` We've sought a different vocabulary for dealing with a very complex subject. We've tried to find a common ground for ministering to people about it.'' The newly prepared statement, expected to be approved in a final presentation to a policy-making general board in June, acknowledges keen diversity among the denomination's 1.6 million members on the issue. Howevever, the statement breaks with the previous 1981 stand, which saw abortion in terms of religious liberty as a `` matter of responsible personal choice.'' The new document, recognizing `` life as a sacred and gracious gift of God,'' says: `` As American Baptists we oppose abortion, as a means of avoiding responsibility for conception, as a primary means of birth control, without regard for the far-reaching consequences of the act. `` We denounce irresponsible sexual behavior and acts of sexual violence that contribute to the large number of abortions each year. `` We grieve with all who struggle with the difficult circumstances that lead them to consider abortion. Recognizing that each person is ultimately responsible to God, we encourage women and men in these circumstances to seek spiritual counsel as they prayerfully and conscientiously consider their decision.'' A sister church, the larger 14.6-million Southern Baptist Convention, takes a firmly anti-abortion position, toughening that stand in 1984 to ask for laws prohibiting all abortion except to `` save the physical life of the mother.'' Changes also have come among more liberal mainline bodies, including: The Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> -RRB- in 1985 qualified its acceptance of choice in the matter, opposing abortion `` as a method of birth control'' or for `` convenience or to ease embarrassment.'' The Church of the Brethren in 1984 explicitly condemned abortion, after previously taking a more pastoral view of it. The former <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, now merged into the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, in 1980 sharpened its rejection of abortion, saying it destroys life, and urged laws protecting it `` from conception to birth.'' Numerous denominations have steadily rejected abortion, including Eastern Orthodox churches, Roman Catholicism, the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod, Mormons and conservative evangelical denominations. However, several mainline bodies, such as the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Disciples of Christ -RRB-, uphold choice about abortion, and the legalizing of it. The seven-member American Baptist task force, including three supporters of legalized abortion, three opponents and one undetermined about it, has held hearings across the country, gathered questionaires and a flood of letters. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Mild </PERSON>, staff assistant on the project at the denomination's headquarters in <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said there has been some discontent with the previous stance of 1981 `` Enough people were not happy'' with it as `` reflecting where we really are,'' she said. The revision expresses no opinion of the 1973 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision legalizing abortion, neither for nor against, but condemns harassing either abortion clinics or doctors refusing to do abortions. The seven-page statement stresses education and ministry to reinforce responsible sexuality, to help those facing problem pregnancies and to provide needed financial aid to women carrying such pregnancies to birth. While not citing any circumstances that justify abortion, as was done previously, the new statement urges a ministry of `` love and spiritual counsel to those who choose to terminate their pregnancies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 8</NOTE>
