<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Stand and Deliver, b0304</HEAD>
<HEAD>``Miami Vice'' Star Goes Home to Make Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The working class neighborhood that taught <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON> respect for humanity and watched the `` Miami Vice'' star mature into an acclaimed actor is home to his latest movie. <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON> returned to an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> high school last spring to make `` Stand and Deliver,'' a movie about a magnetic, demanding math teacher who led an unruly Hispanic class to academic triumph in 1982. The 41-year-old actor was no stranger to the halls of <ORGANIZATION> Garfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. His cousin teaches computer science there. Only 1 -LCB- miles from his childhood home, it is ethnically mixed, like the neighborhood he remembers. `` Stand and Deliver'' was a smash when it opened in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. It brought in $ 411,000 during its first week last month, averaging $ 14,000 at each of 30 theaters, he said. <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON>, an actor of <PERSON> Mexican-American </PERSON> heritage who won an Emmy Award for his role as Lt. <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> series `` Miami Vice,'' was delighted with the movie and its reception in his home area. `` This film is probably the most inspirational film I've done to date,'' he said of the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> release. `` Stand and Deliver'' is about overcoming racial stigmas. It advances the humanities, something <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON> said he holds close to his heart; something he learned in a family of eight living in a neighborhood crowded with <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION>, Mexican, Jewish and American Indian families. <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON>, who co-produced and helped write the movie, claims he is not making a political point. `` I'm not a political animal,'' he said. It's the advancement of the humanities through acting that inspires <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON>. `` It's always been that way. It serves me well and makes me stronger,'' he said. `` That does n't mean I have to make message movies. I think that art forms, especially films, should be used to entertain. Now if by chance your entertaining and allowing -LRB- your audience -RRB- to experience an event that has some value and some substance and some awareness to it, well even better. `` The criterion, No. 1, is the story. If that story happens to be socially relevant, well that's wonderful, but if it is n't, that's OK too.'' `` Stand and Deliver'' is about an event that drew national attention to <ORGANIZATION> Garfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s 1982 calculus class. The predominantly Hispanic class took and passed an Advance Placement calculus test, in stark contrast to the rest of the school, which faced loss of accreditation. The 18 students, who were badgered and inspired by computer specialist-turned-teacher <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>, were stripped of their honors when the <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which tests <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students and provides their scores to colleges and universities, accused the entire class of cheating. In the movie, <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON>, in his role as <PERSON> Escalante </PERSON>, accuses the Educational Testing Service of racism. Students from wealthy <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> would not be questioned if they passed an Advance Placement calculus test, but students with Hispanic names from a barrio high school were suspect, he says in the movie. Eventually, the students are vindicated with a second test. The movie is not meant to be manipulative, <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON> said. It presents an event `` that allows you to experience with your own values.'' `` We do n't give results,'' he said. `` We only give the facts.''
</TEXT>
