<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, April 16-17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bonneville SSE An Impressive Road Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Pontiac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> is more than a technology buff's dream come true. It's an impressive road car and comfortable large sedan that even a techno-phobe can appreciate. Inside the aerodynamically styled vehicle, a driver can tune the radio without taking his hands off the steering wheel. The radio buttons are built into the wheel, around the horn. An electronic compass senses the earth's magnetic field. Thus, changes in the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION>'s direction are continuously displayed on an electronic map on the dashboard. And a new, smooth, fuel-injected 3800 V6, wonderfully firm suspension, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> GT +4 radial tires and antilock brakes join to provide stable road handling and enjoyable ride Yes, the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> is a car to show off to friends and neighbors. But it does n't come cheaply. Base price is $ 21,879. You get what you pay for: The <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> is so loaded with standard equipment there are only three options -LRB- alarm system, interior leather and power sunroof -RRB-. Additionally, the SSE is priced below many of its foreign competitors, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000, which starts at more than $ 22,000, and <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION> 760, which starts around $ 31,200. New for the 1988 model year, the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> is the top of the <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> line which was redesigned inside and out for the 1987 model year. The lowest-priced <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION>, the LE, has a base price of $ 14,099 and nearly the same stylish exterior as the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> but without the fancy handling package and technology frills. There's also a middle offering _ the <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> SE </LOCATION> that starts at $ 16,299 and shares the new 3.8-liter V6 with the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> but not the same suspension. <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, expects to build only 14,000 Bonneville SSEs this model year, and spokesman <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> says, `` We expect to sell them all with no problem. The initial reception to the car has been great, exceeding our forecast.'' <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> projects total Bonneville sales this model year of 110,000, up from 93,575 in the 1987 model year, he added. Bonnevilles rank third in volume at <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, behind the Grand Am and Pontiac 6000 models. The majority of buyers targeted for the 1988 <PERSON> Bonnevilles </PERSON> are male and married, <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> says. Average age is 49 for the LE and 45 for the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION>. The division looks for 44 percent of the LE buyers and 64 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> buyers to be college graduates. Average household income of targeted buyers is $ 41,000 for the LE and $ 61,000 for the <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION>. Many of these -LRB- SSE -RRB- buyers are intenders of high-level imports who previously have n't had a domestic choice, the division said. They're attracted to very expressive styling and are very discriminating in quality and function of features. The test <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SSE </ORGANIZATION> was fun, though there were a few glitches. At night, the dashboard lit up like a Christmas tree because of all the electronics and buttons, including those for automatic heat and air conditioning. However, one of the buttons for setting interior temperature sometimes stuck. An electronic screen on the dashboard indicated when the next oil change, tire rotation and tune-up were needed and monitored doors and the trunk to make sure they were secured. But I drove 5 miles with the trunk ajar, and no warning appeared on the screen. The 10-way, adjustable front bucket seats were roomy and had countless comfortable settings, including three buttons for power lumbar support at three different spots in the back of the seats. But the power headrests were bulkier than I was used to and I found myself craning to look around them when backing up. Still, the trunk was flat and spacious, and the <LOCATION> Delco </LOCATION> sound system was superb. There was comfortable seating in the rear, and a rear arm rest-console provided a spot for beverages and storage if only two people rode back there. However, because the model is so new, Consumer Reports does not yet have repair records.
</TEXT>
