<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New college graduates this spring will face a tight job market, with competition-conscious companies less willing to offer extended on-the-job training, a veteran placement professional says. `` Employers ... today have neither the time nor inclination to ` bring somebody along' gradually,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Challenger </PERSON>, president of Chicago-based Challenger, <ORGANIZATION> Gray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which descibes itself as the nation's oldest outplacement firm. An increasingly competitive marketplace is facing all companies, <PERSON> Challenger </PERSON> said in an analysis of the 1988 college graduate job outlook, released Monday.
