<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0560</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates are not headed skyward despite a slight uptick in recent weeks, economists say. Interest rates rise when lenders become fearful of inflation, but so far inflation remains under control in spite of surprisingly strong economic growth, a number of economists interviewed Tuesday said. Consumer prices are rising at an annual rate of between 4 percent and 4.5 percent, roughly the same as they have for the past three years. And that has allowed Americans to enjoy a rare combination of fairly robust growth and slowly rising prices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> fired one of its longtime advertising agencies, and a source familiar with the decision said it was because the tobacco and foods giant was upset with a no-smoking ad that the agency recently made for another client, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. The agency is <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has been making <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> cookie ads for 12 years and Life Saver candy ads for 18 years. Industry sources estimated Tuesday the agency was handling about $ 100 million in advertising billings for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>, making it a major account by ad industry standards.
