<HEAD>Prices Drop Sharply, Volume Light</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have skidded below the $ 17-a-barrel range following a Kuwaiti news report that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s pricing committee would not recommend a full ministerial conference of the cartel at its April 9 meeting On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the May delivery price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil fell 22 cents per barrel to $ 16.79 on Tuesday. Most of the drop came in the afternoon, but volume was relatively light. Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale No. 2 heating oil fell 0.80 cent a gallon to 45.20 cents, and unleaded gasoline fell 0.71 cent a gallon to 48.64 cents. The oil market has been focusing on Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' price and production policies because of a persistent output glut and widespread reports of cheating among the cartel's 13 members on their self-imposed production limits. The April 9 meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> had incited some hope that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> would act aggressively to stabilize prices and enforce production discipline to limit excessive supplies. Traders said the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> news report dampened the optimism and forced a selloff in the futures market. But they said the light volume of trading suggested most oil market participants are reluctant to buy or sell pending the outcome of the price committee meeting. The committee has no power to alter <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> policy but it can call for a full ministerial meeting, considered its strongest option.
