<HEAD>In Search Of The Perfect Grass Seed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funk </ORGANIZATION>'s grass has shimmered in the Rose Bowl, in Yankee Stadium, on the Masters golf course and across thousands of private lawns. He's got a famous touch with turf, but the 59-year-old researcher and academician says the grass is always greener somewhere else. `` You start out with a variety and then immediately start working on a replacement that's better, because nothing is perfect,'' he said. Colleagues and others involved in the turf industry say <ORGANIZATION> Funk </ORGANIZATION> has taken an unknown field and made it his own, revolutionizing the development of grass and gaining international prominence in the process. A <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researcher and turf science professor, <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> has been developing scores of grass varieties for more than 20 years. In his <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brunswick </ORGANIZATION> offices and on 200 acres of test fields in <LOCATION> Adelphia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> combines various strains of grass seed in search of the best combination. <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> has created fine-textured turf grasses, lush dark green grasses, shade and drought-tolerant grasses, and grasses that repel disease and insects, bearing such names as Rebel, Gator and Prelude. `` He is often referred to as the <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> of the seed industry,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Lofts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>. `` There is nobody, probably in the world, who is as knowledgeable on new varieties in the turf grass industry.'' <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>, who has done business with and consulted <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> for about 20 years, said <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>'s students are courted heavily by the grass seed industry because of his track record. <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>'s work and the work of students and faculty in the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> soils and crops department at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> have kept hundreds of thousands of dollars in royalties flowing into the university's turf research department `` He's one of these fellows who's intelligent and he works efficiently,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>, who retired two years ago after serving as a long-time professor of turf science at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION>. `` He works lots of hours and he's put it all together,'' said <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>, a 25-year associate of Funk. When the golf world's luminaries descend on the <ORGANIZATION> Augusta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> course in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> for the Masters Tournament on Thursday, they will tread a course seeded partly with <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> strain, named after golf legend <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>. The strain carpets many courses throughout the Northeast, <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Adelphi </ORGANIZATION> bluegrass, a hybrid of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> bluegrass, long has been used by groundskeepers at <LOCATION> Shea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Flushing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said stadium manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>. `` It's a sturdy grass and ideal for the temperature of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> gravitated to turf research after an early life dominated by agriculture. He was raised on a 600-acre dairy farm in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, and earned undergraduate and master's degrees in agronomy from <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. After earning his doctorate from <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> in 1961, <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> narrowly missed getting an appointment to research sugarcane growth in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. But the miss freed him to become <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION>' first full-time scientist working with turf grasses. He said his first creation to achieve widescale popularity was the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> perennial rye grass in 1967, which was considered a marked improvement over other rye grasses. <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> said that grass still is used in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> soccer stadiums. This spring, <ORGANIZATION> Funk </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pinnacle </ORGANIZATION> grass _ which is resistant to a number of insects _ should start cropping up on lawns, parks and cemeteries in the Northeast. Over the past 20 years, <PERSON> Funk </PERSON> has become highly regarded for his ability to adapt grasses to the needs of different climates and situations, said <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>, of Lofts Seeds. But <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>'s colleagues say he never is satisfied, and they repeatedly are disarmed by his humility despite his grand reputation and stellar credentials. `` He's the first one we've looked to,'' said <PERSON> Morrissey </PERSON>. `` The great leader is <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>, who has developed probably more proprietary turf types than any one in the world.''
