<FIRST>r f PM-InterestRates Bjt   04-06 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interest Rates, Bjt,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Climb, But Economists Unconcerned</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY77 of Tuesday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates have edged higher in recent weeks, but most economists see no cause for alarm because there is little evidence that the driving force of the rise is higher inflation. Inflation remains under control in spite of surprisingly strong economic growth, economists say. `` There is a lot of skepticism about inflation. I think it's healthy but probably unwarranted,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, vice president and economics director for <ORGANIZATION> ASB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based pension fund manager, said Tuesday Consumer prices are rising at an annual rate of about 4 percent to 4.5 percent, roughly the same as in the past three years. The concern about inflation is a sharp contrast to opinions that prevailed after the Oct. 19 stock market crash. Then, interest rates fell because investors felt the crash might trigger a recession and curb inflation. Rates for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages fell from about 11.6 percent just before the stock market crash last October to a little over 9.8 percent by February, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>. Instead of crashing, though, the economy has created more than 1 million jobs since October. The jobless rate fell to 5.6 percent in March, the lowest in nine years. Some investors changed their minds and decided the economy was in danger of overheating and high inflation. Mortgage rates consequently have crept back to just over 10 percent nationwide as of April 1, <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> says. Inflation fears drive up interest rates because investors demand higher yields to make up for the erosion of the value of fixed-income investments that inflation causes. Americans are paying unusually high interest rates now because credit-market investors were burned by double-digit inflation in the 1970s and early 1980s and keep thinking those days might come again. Despite the fears of last October, many economists now have concluded the stock market crash was good for the economy because it cooled off an economy that was overheating. Steep recessions generally are preceded by inflationary overheating, which leads to high interest rates that in turn choke off economic growth. In the current economy, inflation has n't had a chance to accelerate because the credit markets have reacted so quickly to it, driving up interest rates and cooling the economy before it overheats, said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON>, a managing director and financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In a sense, <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> said, the economy has become self-correcting through the bond market's sensitivity to inflation. That may explain why the economy remains in the longest peacetime expansion of the 20th century. `` The bond market is running the economic show both globally and domestically,'' <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> said. `` Bond managers, in effect, are in the driver's seat.'' Some economists believe the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's central bank, has engineered the recent uptick in interest rates According to that theory, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is trying to prove its inflation-fighting credentials to the bond market. It is heading off a steep rise in interest rates over the long term by pushing them up slightly in the short term. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reaction is appropriate,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gols </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Little </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` To prepare for inflationary surges is much better than to do it afterward.'' But other economists say <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> action, if any, has been modest. One reason might be that any attempt by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to cool off the economy with higher interest rates would punish the housing market, which is relatively weak. If the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is doing anything, `` They're just raising the flag and saying, ` Hey, we're here. We're not oblivious to what's going on in the world,''' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandross </PERSON>, chief economist in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> head office of <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>. The yield of the widely watched 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond has ticked up to about 8.9 percent this week from a recent low of less than 8.3 percent in early February. <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> said the bond probably would go no higher than 9.3 percent and no lower than 8.3 percent in the rest of 1988. <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> said it might edge up to 9.5 or even 9.7 percent by the end of the year. Gols, who is in a small minority of economists predicting a recession by the end of 1988, predicted the long bond's yield would rise slightly and then trend steadily downward.
</TEXT>
