<HEAD>Appeals Court Sides With Koppers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has upheld a victory for <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in its fight against a $ 1.7 billion hostile takeover attempt by British industrialist <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> and the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> said its board of directors decided it could not take a position on the outstanding hostile bid by the Beazer group because of the court ruling, other outstanding litigation and <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> ongoing attempts to seek alternative courses of action. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> Judges <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pregerson </PERSON> late Tuesday denied the <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> group's appeal of a lower court order issued Monday that blocked its $ 60 a share hostile tender offer. The one-sentence ruling was announced from the appeal court's headquarters in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> issued a preliminary injunction suspending the tender offer indefinitely because of on antitrust questions. He issued the order after <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> argued that competition could be weakened in the local market for sand, gravel and hard stone for construction if <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> properties of <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> were combined. Attorneys for the <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> group had argued that a delay in closing the tender offer could jeopardize financing for the takeover. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> shares declined $ 1 to $ 56.25 a share Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> met Tuesday with <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON>, neither `` was prepared to discuss much of mutual interest at that meeting,'' <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> stated in a news release. <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> requested the meeting, according to <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> was not prepared to discuss the hostile tender offer or <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal to negotiate a friendly merger with the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> construction materials and chemicals company, she said. <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON>, on the other hand, declined to discuss anything but the takeover or a friendly deal. <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> testifying before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> in a hearing on <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' lawsuit contending the <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> group violated securities laws in launching its tender offer March 3. The offer expires at midnight EDT Thursday. <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> issued no ruling Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> has disputed the accuracy of disclosures made in documents issued in conjunction with the tender offer. In his testimony, <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> identified documents suggesting <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' chemicals businesses could be sold after the takeover for as much as $ 700 million. The takeover plan calls for getting at least $ 400 million for those operations, although <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> said no serious bidders had yet been found.
