<HEAD>Japanese, U.S. Construction Firms Launch Joint Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Fujita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a major Japanese construction firm, has launched an equally-owned joint venture with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> design engineering firm, a <ORGANIZATION> Fujita </ORGANIZATION> official said today. <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON>'s linkup with Los Angeles-based <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mendenhall </PERSON> is the first such joint construction venture established between Japanese and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms, said <PERSON> Hajime </PERSON> <PERSON> Shigeoka </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON> spokesman. <ORGANIZATION> DMJM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fujita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, headed by <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON> President <PERSON> Kazuaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON>, will conduct market research in and outside <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and will gather information on construction technologies, <PERSON> Shigeoka </PERSON> said. The new firm also will plan, design, supervise and undertake contruction projects. <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> DMJM </ORGANIZATION> have engaged in technological cooperation since 1965, according to <LOCATION> Shigeoka </LOCATION>. `` We will jointly launch business activities to cope with a new age,'' <PERSON> Shigeoka </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Fujita </PERSON> as saying. <PERSON> Shigeoka </PERSON> said the new company, with a capital of about $ 80,600, was set up on Feb. 22 in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The announcement of the venture was delayed as company officials watched developments in U.S.-Japan talks on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s construction market. The construction issue has caused friction in trade relations between the two nations, with many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies contending they are virtually shut out of the Japanese construction market while Japanese compan