<HEAD>Intel Unveils New Generation Of Microchips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A research team for <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has developed a new series of microchips capable of executing 7.5 million instructions per second, the company has announced. The microchips, known as the 80960 family, are designed for such uses as helping control robots, airplanes, automobiles and telecommunications, according to <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microcomputer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The microchips perform at two to three times the speed of previous microchip generations used for similar machine-controlling operations, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. In industrial markets, the chips are expected to supplement or replace other <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> chips that have been available for as long as 10 years, he said Tuesday. The new chips' circuitry incorporates about 500,000 transistors into a half-inch square of silicon. The circuitry involves parallel architecture that allows the chip or a combination of chips to attack various parts of a problem simultaneously, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. Unlike <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION>'s standard microprocessor and its predecessors, the new chip is programmed only once for a specific function, he said. Two of the new chips were designed for commercial use and the other two are for military applications, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said.
