<HEAD>W. Russell Boss, Former President of Cross Pen Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON>, a former president and chairman of penmaker <ORGANIZATION> A.T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has died at age 79. Boss died Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Holy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>. Boss began working as sales manager and treasurer of Cross in 1937, shortly after the death of his father <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, owner of the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island-based </LOCATION> company. Over the next 27 years, Boss rose to become chairman and president of the company and helped it evolve from a private, family-owned business with a dozen employees to a public company with $ 155.4 million in revenue and more than 1,400 employees worldwide. Boss in 1979 relinquished the chairmanship he had held since 1971 to his eldest son, <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON>, R.I. He remained vice chairman until 1985, when he was named chairman emeritus. The Providence, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, native served on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s governing board and bred thoroughbred horses in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Boss was survived by his wife <PERSON> Doris </PERSON>, two sons, a sister and six grandchidren. Services were scheduled for Saturday in <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, R.I.
