<FIRST>r f PM-WorkerComp     04-06 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Worker Comp,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: Model Worker Ineligible For Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> does not have to pay worker compensation to a model employee who fainted, struck his head and suffered severe and permanent brain damage after being told he was being demoted. The court ruled Tuesday in a case involving <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who had worked for <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> for 19 years and was described by his supervisor, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Enk </PERSON>, as a good, punctual employee who never complained and appeared to enjoy his work. `` We conclude that claimant's physical injury did not result from an unexpected, unusual, or extraordinary stress related to employment,'' Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> wrote in the three-member court's unanimous ruling. `` The physical injury is therefore noncompensable as an industrial injury.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulman </PERSON>, called Tuesday's decision `` disappointing but not too surprising'' in light of precedents and said he anticpated an appeal to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who is described as being in a vegatative state, was injured Aug. 8, 1985 when <PERSON> Enk </PERSON> told him that he was being reassigned in a cost-cutting move to a job that required different skills and carried a one-third cut in pay. The change also meant working for a new manager reputed to be a strict disciplinarian and about whom <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> already had expressed concern. `` Enk turned to walk away, and claimaint took two or three steps after him,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> wrote. `` Enk then turned back to speak with claimant again and saw him falling straight over backwards. Claimant's head struck the tile-covered concrete floor causing permanent brain damage.'' Rumors about pending job cuts had been circulating at <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> for one or two months, and <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> was worried about financial problems if he were displaced, according to court records. He also feared a new job might lead to a recurrence of earlier, work-related hernia problems. Expert witnesses who testified on <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s behalf said the faint stemmed from emotional shock and his present condition was unlikely to improve. But the judges said previous state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings made it clear that physical injuries caused by job-related emotional stress need not be compensated `` unless the stress is unusual, unexpected or extraordinary.'' And they said that threatened economic hardship, `` including such naturally traumatic events as layoffs and plant closures, may indeed expose the affected workers to varying degrees of emotional distress, but are not sufficiently unexpected, unusual or extraordinary in modern society to warrant compensability as an industrial injury.'' A switchboard operator at <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s Phoenix-area headquarters said no one was available for comment immediately.
</TEXT>
