<FIRST>r f PM-FreeDrugs     04-06 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Free Drugs,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Prescription Drugs To Treat Heart Disease Available Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> G.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is broadening its program to give free drugs to the the poor to include all of its medication for heart disease. Last year, <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> began providing its high blood pressure medicine to people who could not afford to buy it and had no insurance. Now, all seven of its drugs that treat cardiovascular problems will be available to poor people without charge, said Dr. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer. `` I personally believe that all drugs that treat life-threatening diseases should be involved,'' <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Tuesday. `` But cardiovascular drugs are about all we make.'' No one who suffers from cardiovascular disease should be denied medication because they ca n't afford it, he said. <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>, which is based in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION><LOCATION> , </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, is inviting all physicians in the nation to participate in the program, which cost the company $ 9 million last year. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Greener </PERSON>, a senior vice president, said <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> does not know how much the expanded program will cost, but he said the company expects it will double the existing program. `` There's no money limit on it,'' he said. <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON> said the company will deliver $ 1 million worth of certificates to clinics and hospitals in 10 major cities today to dramatize the expansion of its `` Patient in Need'' program. Any physician, clinic or hospital in the nation may request Searle certificates for needy patients. The company sets broad guidelines for patients to qualify but leaves it up to the individual physician to make the decision. The company is mailing instructions to doctors that classify poor people as those with annual household incomes of $ 8,000 for one or two people, or $ 11,000 for three or more family members. To qualify, patients must not have insurance or other assistance that would pay for the drug. `` It's up to the doctor to determine, but the patient does n't have to bring in tax returns or anything like that,'' said <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON> `` We believe the doctor knows who his poor patients are.'' <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> launched the pilot program with two drugs that treat high blood pressure in February 1987. Twenty-thousand patients have received free medication. The new expanded program includes five additional products used to treat high blood pressure, angina, arrhythmias and congestive heart failure. `` The American pharmaceutical industry can satisfy the unmet prescription needs of the medically indigent patient population in this country,'' <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Judee </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that all pharmaceutical companies do something but <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> is more extensive at working with the health-care delivery system. She said the other companies will help out in individual need cases or in third-world countries. But she said she knows of no other pharmaceutical company doing the same kind of work as <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> is a research-based company which develops, manufactures and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide. It is a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Two-thirds of <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s sales are in cardiovascular drugs, <PERSON> Greener </PERSON> said. The other third is primarily oral contraceptives, he said.
