<HEAD>EEC Finds No Signs of Economic Recession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite a slight drop in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s economic sentiment indicator in February, the 12-nation trading bloc is not heading for a recession, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, citing the latest business and consumer survey, said there were `` no signs of an approaching recession.'' It said the stock market crash and the turbulence on foreign-exchange markets last fall affected `` economic performance less than originally feared.'' The commission said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s economic indicator, which is based partly on the results of the survey, dropped to 102.7 in February from 102.9 in January, but was above the 102.6 level recorded in November 1987 after the October crash. The indicator comprises an industrial confidence indicator, a construction confidence indicator, a consumer confidence indicator and stock price indexes. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> economists reported that production expectations continued to point toward further growth over the next few months, while the outlook for exports looked brighter than anticipated. Lower-than-expected production results in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since last December have led industrialists there to revise their production expectations significantly downward, the commission said. The consumer confidence indicator lost a point in February over the preceding month, and consumers remained cautious about purchasing durables, the commission said. Retailers also continued to feel slightly pessimistic about future prospects, but their assessment of the overall business situation remained positive, according to the report.
