<HEAD>Cable Shopping Service Suffers $20 Million Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Fashion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> home shopping service reported a first-year loss of $ 20 million and announced the departure of its chairman and chief executive. The company, which sells clothes, cosmetics and accessories over cable television, had sales of $ 5.5 million in its first four months of operation, according to the announcement Tuesday. The Fashion Channel, which formed about a year ago and went on the air in October, announced that co-founder <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gee </PERSON> would no longer serve as chairman and chief executive officer. Gee was the last of three founding top executives to leave the management. In January, the company announced the departures of <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klauer </PERSON>, a former May Co.. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> president, and <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Gee will remain as a director. Fashion Channel's newly named president, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, said he has been talking to several parties interested in buying part of the company, including <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, which is backed by <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Penney </PERSON> and STN of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> QVC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Value </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. `` The company is still operating,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` It's busniess as usual and we're holding down the fort But it's not fun.'' The company attributed much of the loss to start-up costs. The company's stock took a drastic plunge in the October market crash, just over two weeks after it was first offered to the public. Since then, Fashion Channel has been forced to move merchandise by cutting prices drastically, said analyst <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerbrandt </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gerbrandt </PERSON> also blamed the loss in part on overbuying of goods that proved unattractive to customers.
