<HEAD>South American Leaders Meet To Discuss Economies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The presidents of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> met Wednesday for the fifth time in three years to discuss ways to unify their economies. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> met with <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanguinetti </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest countries _ have been meeting since 1985 on ways to integrate their economies along the lines of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. So far, 21 agreements have been signed between the two countries. On Thursday, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> plan to sign additional pacts eliminating trade tariffs for automobiles, automotive parts and food goods. Neighboring <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> so far has been mostly an active observer in the project.
</TEXT>
