loss of their power under the Conservative government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> _ which has introduced union-curbing legislation that, for example, requires unions to ballot their members before calling a strike. The deals are strongly opposed by <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s largest union. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, general secretary of the electricians union, known as the EETPU, has threatened several times to ballot his 336,000 members on pulling out of the <ORGANIZATION> TUC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> has the support of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, who also has warned that he would try to bring his 857,000-strong union out of the <ORGANIZATION> TUC </ORGANIZATION> if he were prevented from signing more of the controversial deals. The AEU is the country's second-largest union.
