<FIRST>u f AM-US-Airbus     04-06 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Airbus,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Europeans Risk Trade Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told the governments of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> on Wednesday they are risking a trade war by their `` enormous subsidies'' to <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> passenger planes. The major trade bill now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would permit the charging of extra `` countervailing'' duties on imports of the Airbus. They would be designed to compensate for the subsidies, raising the price of the foreign planes and thus improving the chances of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft manufacturers making sales to airlines here. `` The longer these governments delay in coming to grips with their own subsidies for <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION>, the more they heighten the risk of a major trade conflict,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said in a statement. With the statement, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s office distributed a detailed refutation of a report on March 18 by <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION>, the consortium that makes the planes, on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidies to aircraft manufacturers. He criticized the report as containing `` poor scholarship and false conclusions.'' It said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government had provided about $ 23 billion in direct and indirect subsidies over the past decade to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade officials have long complained that the European subsidies give <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> aircraft builders an unfair advantage over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> does not directly support civil aircraft programs,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` It is the four <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> governments that have lavished gigantic sums on Airbus for nearly two decades despite the program's inability to show any profit.'' He said he expects to see members of the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> governments in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in mid-May and would like to discuss indirect subsidies before then. `` We will not hold such discussions on the basis of a ` study' that has no credibility,'' he said After the last negotiations at <ORGANIZATION> Constance </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, on March 18, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said a first step had been taken in a prospective agreement on production subsidies but that there was still a long way to go on subsidies for research and development. The statement issued by <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s office said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government buys goods for its own needs and not to benefit any manufacturer. When major contractors make profits, they can spend them as they will, it added. `` By contrast, the Airbus partners must spend the money supplied to them by their governments on commercial airplane development and nothing else,'' the statement said.
