 Japanese investors bought $ 12.77 billion worth of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> real estate in 1987, a 70 percent increase over the previous year, according to a new report. The purchases were concentrated in markets traditionally favored by the Japanese _ <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ but investors are broadening their sights to include other areas as well, according to a study released Wednesday. The study, conducted for the last three years by <ORGANIZATION> Kenneth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laventhal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide accounting firm, is based on information from clients, public records and other sources, and is described by the company as a slight underestimation. The buying binge is spurred by the rising value of the yen in relation to the dollar, the tight real estate market in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and attractive rates of return on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial real estate ranging from 6 percent to 9 percent a year, said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodman </PERSON>, managing partner of the company's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> office. Japanese real estate purchases mushroomed in the three years of the study: $ 1.86 billion in 1985, $ 7.53 billion in 1986 and $ 12.77 billion in 1987. In 1987, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> was the favorite shopping spot, attracting $ 3.3 billion from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the study found. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> was second, with $ 2.98 billion, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was third, with $ 2.34 billion. Far behind, in order, were <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Office buildings commanded the most dollars from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ $ 5.19 billion in 1987. Investment in hotel and resort properties soared 160 percent in 1987, to $ 4.57 billion, partly because of several big purchases in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Investment in residential property was $ 1.3 billion. The study found increasing Japanese interest in so-called secondary real estate markets, including <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. For the first time in the three years of the study, 56 percent of the purchases were in secondary markets.
