<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market rolled up one of its biggest gains of the year today, taking its cue from a stronger dollar and a decline in interest rates. The market took off in the early afternoon after trading in a narrow range earlier in the day. Analysts said the gain was due to a strengthening of the dollar in foreign exchange trading, which in turn prompted a decline in interest rates. The dollar moved higher, they said, on speculation that the major industrial nations may be moving toward a reaffirmation of support for the currency against the Japanese yen. A meeting is planned for next week. Such an agreement could mean that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would no longer feel it necessary to tighten its credit policy and push interest rates higher in a bid to head off inflation. The advance in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average of 30 industrials was so strong that it triggered for the first time a voluntary plan under which the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> hopes to curb price volatility.
