<HEAD>Stock Market Posts Year's Second-Biggest Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market surged Wednesday, putting in its second-best performance so far this year after taking a cue from a stronger dollar and lower interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 16.91 on Tuesday, jumped another 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67. It was the biggest rise in the key blue-chip indicator since it climbed 76.42 points on Jan. 4, the first trading day of the year. Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 3 to 1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 189.76 million shares, compared with 135.29 million on Tuesday. The Dow's advance was so strong it triggered a 50-point voluntary restriction on computerized program trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for the first time since the limit was announced Feb. 4. Program trading, a technique used by brokerages to profit on price differences between stocks and the corresponding stock-index futures, has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market and frightening investors. The market climbed steadily throughout the afternoon after trading in a narrow range earlier in the day. Analysts said the gain was due to a strengthening of the dollar in foreign exchange trading, which in turn prompted a decline in interest rates in the credit markets. The dollar moved higher, they said, on speculation that the major industrial nations may be moving toward a fresh agreement to support the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. A meeting of the industrial powers is planned for next week. Such an agreement could mean that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would no longer feel it necessary to tighten its credit policy and push interest rates higher in a bid to head off inflation.
