<HEAD>Chrysler UAW Council Agreeing to Fall Into Pattern with GM, Ford</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers voted Wednesday to seek the job protections and economic benefits won by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union in contracts signed last fall with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` We've had a pattern settlement before us now for almost a year. ... It should not take a long time for us to put this together,'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> told reporters after addressing the 140-member <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> national <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> agreed to open talks early _ April 18 instead of mid-July _ after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to sell its 28,000-worker <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary sparked bitter worker opposition. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> backed down from the sale in early March, shortly after the issue erupted, but decided the damage left in its wake would intensify if the two sides waited until July to meet at the bargaining table. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said he did n't believe the rift would hurt the chance of an early settlement mirroring the industry-pattern <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> contracts. `` I do n't plan on sitting in early negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> from the time we open here in April until Sept. 14,'' when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s contract expires, <PERSON> Bieber </PER