e identified, called the opposition selfish and argued that the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> workers already are part of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, which bought <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> last year. Proposals approved Wednesday would, like the pattern <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> contracts, forbid plant closings not announced before the start of negotiations. The union's proposals for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also would ban sale of plants or other operations, according to the printed resolutions approved by the council. The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> agreements also forbid layoffs for any reason except slow sales of a product. The exception, seen as a loophole by many workers, has allowed <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> to indefinitely close plants that make products whose sales were lagging. But <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said any loophole would most likely be addressed in 1990 talks rather than at the Chrysler table this year. Under the pattern, workers also will receive bonuses equal to 3 percent of their 1988 and 1989 earnings and a share of sales-generated profits if their companies' earn above a set amount. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> also wants to increase its representation on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors _ already unique in the auto industry _ from one seat to four The current seat belongs to the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> president, and <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said it gives him an extra chance to try influencing some corporate decisions that affect his members. With three other <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members on the board, <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> joked, `` It would n't be a 19-1 vote anymore. I'm convinced I could convince my -LRB- UAW -RRB- colleagues to vote with me.''
