<FIRST>u f AM-FreeDrugs Bjt   04-06 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Free Drugs, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searle Expands Free Drug Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> G.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it will expand a program of giving heart disease drugs to the poor, a move observers say puts the company at the helm of the pharmaceutical industry's efforts to help the indigent Under a year-old pilot program, Skokie-based <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> gave $ 9 million worth of high blood pressure medicine to 20,000 patients. The company said it would expand its `` Patient In Need'' program by making all seven of its heart medicines available. The plan will roughly double the cost and the number of patients involved, company officials said. To kick off its expanded program, <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> planned on Wednesday to deliver $ 1 million worth of certificates for drugs to clinics and hospitals in 10 major cities. `` I personally believe that all drugs that treat life-threatening diseases should be involved,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s chairman and chief executive officer. He noted that congressional sources put the number of Americans without any health insurance at 37 million. <PERSON> Judee </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuler </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said all drug manufacturers do something to help poor patients, `` but <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> is more extensive.'' Most of <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s drugs are cardiovascular medications, and <PERSON> Gilgore </PERSON> called on other pharmaceutical houses to follow suit with their drugs. `` This area is extremely tricky,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Nefi </PERSON>, a spokesman for E.R. <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` Drugs are a commodity rigorously controled by the federal government. It's not like making shoes and giving them to the poor.'' <PERSON> Nefi </PERSON> said he was not familiar with the details of <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s program, but he noted that `` the distribution mechanism is going to be difficult, and I would like to see how they're going to do it. <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s expanded effort will distribute the drugs in the same manner as the pilot program, said spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greener </PERSON>. Participating doctors are issued certificates from <LOCATION> Searle </LOCATION>. Patients receive both a prescription and a certificate, both of which must be presented to a pharmacist. Patients get the drugs for free, while pharmacists mail the certificates to <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> for reimbursement. The company classifies poor people as those with annual household incomes of $ 8,000 for one or two people, or $ 11,000 for three or more family members. To qualify, patients must not have insurance or other assistance that would pay for the drug. Several other drug makers have some form of indigent care program. <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Dohme </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, donates drugs to various charitable groups, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which distributes them to physicians who pass them on to the needy at home and abroad. <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> also will give free drugs to individual doctors who request them for poor patients, said spkeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gellert </PERSON>. `` We feel we give a pretty broadly based coverage,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Roxane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, gives a drug to poor terminal cancer patients in severe pain, said company spokesman <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojta </PERSON>. The company announced its plan several years ago. <ORGANIZATION> Wyeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, has a `` compassionate program for the tryly needy through the physician,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON>. `` It's judged on a patient-by-patient basis.'' <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> is a research-based company that develops, manufactures and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide. It is a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
