<TEXT>
 A federal judge said Wednesday that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> can not proceed with his $ 1.7 billion hostile tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> until at least April 15 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District judge in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on Monday suspended the $ 60-a-share offer indefinitely on antitrust grounds. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> said if <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> succeeds in overturning the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ruling, his order immediately blocks the offer until he rules on <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' arguments that the unwanted suitors violated securities law. <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> said he will rule by April 15 on the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> construction materials and chemicals company's request for a preliminary injunction. It was not immediately clear how this latest barrier would affect the tender offer from <ORGANIZATION> BNS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the takeover company formed by <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Attorneys for the Beazer interests said a delay could scuttle its tender offer. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said Wednesday he expects <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer will be declared inadequate by <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> board of directors. `` My judgment is that with more time we will find that -LRB- the bid -RRB- is inadequate,'' <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> testified in federal court, one day after <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' board said it was reserving judgment on the offer. Under questioning by <ORGANIZATION> BNS </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mishkin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said he also expected someone to beat the $ 60-a-share offer. `` I'm not sure I could hazard a guess as to when'' a better offer might come, <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> said. The chairman said he expected some stockholders would consider $ 60 a share as an adequate offer. He said he also expected some shareholders would want to accept the $ 60 a share. Arbitrageurs likely would tender their stock as well, he said. The offer from <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>, head of the construction and building materials concern <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Shearson </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> was to have expired at midnight Thursday. The two are partners in BNS along with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, which launched the tender offer March 3. <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> told <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> on Wednesday that the board is considering selling an interest in all or part of the company. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> prefers to sell no more than 20 percent to 25 percent of its valued construction materials and services group, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> has said it also is considering a recapitalization plan and, if necessary, the sale of the entire company as a defensive measure. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> director, noted in testimony Tuesday that a recapitalization plan is still in the formative stages. A management-led buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' chemicals businesses also has been considered an alternative to the BNS of