<HEAD>Stocks Move Broadly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fortified by a stronger dollar, lower interest rates and an afternoon of frenzied buying, the stock market soared Wednesday as the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average posted its second biggest gain of the year. But despite the strong gain, some analysts were skeptical about how long it could last. `` It was a very impressive rally, but it's still a manic depressive market, so I'm not trusting it yet for any sustained move,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Czech </PERSON>, head of the investment policy group at the brokerage <ORGANIZATION> Blunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ellis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Loewi </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. The Dow Jones industrials, the market's best-known indicator, advanced 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67. It was the ninth biggest gain ever in the Dow Jones industrials and the largest gain since it climbed 76.42 on Jan. 4. The Dow's gain was so powerful that it triggered a 50-point voluntary restriction on computerized program trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for the first time since the limit was announced Feb. 4. But even after the restriction was triggered, stock prices continued to rise until the market closed. Gainers swamped losers by a margin of nearly 3 to 1 in the overall tally of NYSE-listed issues, with 1,187 up, 414 down and 384 unchanged. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index rose 3.47 to 149.76. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 189.76 million shares, up from 135.29 million shares on Tuesday. The stock market opened with some modest gains but gave most of them back by noontime before sweeping broadly ahead in the early afternoon. Analysts said the trigger for the market's rise was a news report from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> that said officials of the seven major industrial countries are likely to agree on a plan of support for the dollar. A strong dollar would diminish inflationary pressure, and perhaps ease the pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to tighten its credit policy, said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinder </PERSON>, who follows stocks for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION>. Expectations that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would tighten its policy and raise interest rates had been depressing stock market psychology, he said. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, a market watcher for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the dollar's strength soon rippled through the bond market, sending long-term rates lower. That in turn made yields on stocks look more attractive, he said. In each of the markets, he said traders who had sold borrowed contracts in expectations that the dollar, bonds and stocks would fall suddenly saw prices rising and felt compelled to buy in an effort to cut their potential losses. `` Too many people were selling the market short,'' he said. The voluntary restrictions on program trading were called into play after the Dow Jones average passed the 50-point gain mark at about 3:19 p.m. EDT, a spokeswoman for the exchange said. Program trading, a technique used by brokerages to profit on price differences between stocks and the corresponding stock-index futures, has been blamed for injecting volatility into the market and frightening investors. Among actively-traded issues on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATIO