<HEAD>Tycoon Says He Doesn't Want Tax Evasion Sentence Set Aside</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``Posner was'' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with
details from afternoon hearing. Picks up 6th graf pvs, ``The
sentence;'' also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millionaire industrialist <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> said Wednesday he does not want a judge to set aside his setence for tax evasion that grants five years' probation on the condition he set up a $ 3 million program for the homeless. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> responded to a motion filed Monday by a federal prosecutor challenging the legality of that sentence. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> said the court could not force a defendant to make a contribution to `` a non-aggrieved person.'' At a hearing Wednesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> required the 69-year-old <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> to state under oath that he did not wish the sentence set aside and that he was going ahead with the plan `` freely and voluntarily.'' <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s chief attorney, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, must formally reply to <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>'s motion within 30 days. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> heard <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> and a 10-member blue-ribbon committee discuss the program's first stage, a study of homelessness in three southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> counties. `` Since February, I have been studying and learning about the problems of the homeless both nationally and in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> said in a brief statement. Part of his sentence has included work at <ORGANIZATION> Camillus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a refuge for the homeless in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> served food, attended substance abuse meetings and gave out clothing. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> said the study, which is being administered by <ORGANIZATION> Barry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, will examine groups such as alcoholics, the mentally ill and families with children and will review how government policies affect homelessness. Findings of the study are scheduled to be available by mid-May. But he stressed that the study is not the most important element of the program. `` All the studies in the world will not help one homeless person,'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> added. `` I will come to you with what will solve the problem.'' <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> said he did n't plan to take an active role in the committee's work, but he suggested the initial study not use more than $ 250,000 to $ 500,000 of <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s donation. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> said he was ready to deposit the necessary money in any institution directed by the court. The sentence also ordered <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> to pay about $ 4 million in back taxes, penalties, interest and fines for pleading no-contest to 10 counts of tax fraud for inflating the value of land donated to <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Spellman </PERSON> acknowledged when he imposed the sentence that its legality might be questioned. `` If for some reason -LRB- the sentence -RRB- is ever challenged, this court will, in fact, incarcerate <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>,'' he said in February. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> could be sentenced to up to 40 years in prison for the offenses.
