<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that more suitors have come forward since the filmmaking company announced Monday it was considering several unsolicited takeover bids. Separately, the company reported it had reduced its losses by 73 percent for the second quarter and 84 percent for the half, partly because of its successful film `` Moonstruck.'' Disclosure of the new bids came as the company announced a special committee of its board has been formed to weigh the offers. The committee does not include financier <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON>, who owns 79 percent of the company's 50.1 million shares. `` The committee will promptly consider the inquiries received before Monday's announcement, as well as additional inquiries received in the last two days,'' said <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>. The company again declined to identify the suitors or to indicate whether it would be amenable to a takeover, saying only, `` We have a duty to our shareholders to explore these matters.'' Analysts have suggested <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> may be offering to buy the rest of the stock and take the company private. Other likely investors listed by analysts were investors <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, whose separate bids for other companies are stalled and considered unlikely to succeed. <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> had been majority owner of the old <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> studios </ORGANIZATION>, then sold them in 1986 to media entrepreneur <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> for $ 1.5 billion plus assumption of some debt. As part of that deal, <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> immediately repurchased the <LOCATION> UA </LOCATION> segment. Later, <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> sold off all of the <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> unit except for its film library that he is using on his Atlanta-based superstation <ORGANIZATION> WTBS </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kerkorkian </PERSON> purchased the studio and <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar-Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought some other assets. <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> paid a total of $ 730 million to buy back the two segments and has had spotty success in his attempts to rebuild the companies. For its second quarter ended Feb. 29, the comapny posted a net loss of $ 4.6 million, compared with a deficit of $ 17.1 million a year earlier. Revenue for the period rose 48 percent to $ 157.9 million from $ 106.2 million. For the half, the company trimmed its losses to $ 2.6 million from $ 14.4 million, as revenue rose 43 percent to $ 339.9 million from $ 237.2 million.
