<HEAD>Sales Jump For Domestic Automakers In Late March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Buyer incentives and economic confidence boosted late-March and first-quarter sales reported Wednesday by the Big Three automakers. Some import carmakers also reported increases although many posted declines for the March 21-31 sales period and for the quarter, blaming the weaker dollar that effectively raised their prices for American buyers. Domestic car sales totaled 332,721 for the 10 days, up from 282,358 for the nine-day sales period of late March 1987. Domestic sales for the first quarter totaled 1,914,022, up from 1,666,748 a year earlier. Import car sales, reported monthly, totaled 255,867 for March, up from 237,677 in March 1987, and totaled 700,572 for the quarter, up from 639,403 in the 1987 first quarter. First-quarter sales of imported light trucks slid to 168,908 from 204,424 in the 1987 first quarter. Domestic light truck sales jumped to 1,044,984 for the quarter from 840,073 a year earlier. Sales were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 8.4 million for the late March period, up from a strong 8.1 million rate for the period last year, and were 7.5 million for the month, up from 7.3 million for March 1987. `` Sales are robust for the month, continuing what was going on in January and February,'' said <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Certo </PERSON>, analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. She added buyers appeared confident in a strong election-year economy and unworried about last October's stock slump <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> each reported more than 18 percent jumps in daily sales rates for the quarter while <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the top seller, reported a 9.5 percent rise. Dealers incentives helped, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rewey </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> vice president. `` Cash-allowance buyer incentive programs are in effect a temporary price cut and the buyers are reacting to the bargain prices,'' <PERSON> Rewey </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> sold 159,728 domestically produced autos for the 10 days, up from 136,082 in the nine-day late-March period last year, and 942,830 for the quarter, up from 849,470 in the 1987 first quarter. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s daily sales rate was up 9.5 percent. Ford domestic auto sales totaled 93,590 for the 10 days, up from 79,249 a year earlier, and 553,545 for the three months, up from 462,629 for the 1987 first quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> set a record with sales of 150,522 domestically made light trucks for the month of March, up from 132,126 in March 1987 and the most for any March for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> sold 48,125 domestic cars for the 10 days, up from 41,652 in the year-ago period, and 283,491 for the quarter, up from 236,280 in the first quarter of 1987. Some import carmakers also reported increases. For example, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> sales rose to 42,734 for March from 37,099 in March 1987, and 127,050 for the quarter, up from 101,117 in the first quarter of 1987. But Nissan sales slid to 39,536 for the month from 41,824 in March 1987, and to 92,163 for the quarter, down from 119,452 a year ago.
